d Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Westlake High School (Texas) alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-move-indef|small=yes}}\n{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name = Drew Brees \n| image = Drew Brees at Saints Super Bowl parade 2010-02-09.jpg\n| image_size = 225\n| alt =\n| caption = Brees at the Saints' [[Super Bowl XLIV]] victory parade in February 2010\n| current_team = New Orleans Saints \n| number = 9\n| position = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1979|1|15|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Dallas, Texas]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place =\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 0\n| weight_lbs = 209\n| high_school = [[Westlake High School (Texas)|Westlake]] ([[Austin, Texas]])\n| college = [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]]\n| draftyear = 2001\n| draftround = 2\n| draftpick = 32\n| pastteams =\n* [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]] ({{NFL Year|2001}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2005}})\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] ({{NFL Year|2006}}\u2013present)\n| status= Active\n| highlights =\n* [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XLIV|XLIV]])\n* [[Super Bowl MVP]] ([[Super Bowl XLIV|XLIV]])\n* 13\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2005 Pro Bowl|2004]], [[2007 Pro Bowl|2006]], [[2009 Pro Bowl|2008]]\u2013[[2015 Pro Bowl|2014]], [[2017 Pro Bowl|2016]]\u2013[[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2006 All-Pro Team|2006]])\n* 4\u00d7 Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2008 All-Pro Team|2008]], [[2009 All-Pro Team|2009]], [[2011 All-Pro Team|2011]], [[2018 All-Pro Team|2018]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[NFL Offensive Player of the Year]] (2008, 2011)\n* [[Sports Illustrated Sportsman of the Year|''Sports Illustrated'' Sportsman of the Year]] (2010)\n* [[Associated Press Male Athlete of the Year]] (2010)\n* [[Bert Bell Award]] (2009)\n* [[Art Rooney Award]] (2018)\n* [[Walter Payton NFL Man of the Year]] (2006)\n* [[NFL Comeback Player of the Year]] (2004)\n* 7\u00d7 [[List of National Football League season passing yardage leaders|NFL passing yards leader]] (2006, 2008, 2011, 2012, 2014\u20132016)\n* 4\u00d7 [[List of National Football League season passing touchdowns leaders|NFL passing touchdowns leader]] (2008, 2009, 2011, 2012)\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of NFL annual passer rating leaders|NFL passer rating leader]] (2009, 2018)\n* 6\u00d7 [[List of National Football League annual pass completion percentage leaders|NFL completion percentage leader]] (2009\u20132011, 2017, 2018, 2019)\n* [[Bart Starr Award]] (2011)\n*[[Best Record-Breaking Performance ESPY Award]] (2019)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2000)\n* [[Chicago Tribune Silver Football]] (2000)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Big Ten Offensive Player of the Year]] (1998, 2000)\n\n;NFL records<!--Major records only-->\n* [[List of National Football League passing yards leaders|Most career passing yards]]\n* [[List of National Football League career passing completions leaders|Most career pass completions]]\n* [[List of National Football League career passing touchdowns leaders|Most career touchdown passes]]\n* Highest career completion percentage\n* Highest single-season completion percentage\n* Most [[List of most consecutive games with touchdown passes in the National Football League|consecutive games with a touchdown pass]]\n* Most pass completions in a season\n* Most 5,000 passing yard seasons\n* Highest completion percentage in a game\n* [[List of NFL quarterbacks with seven touchdown passes in a game|Most touchdown passes in a game]] (tied)\n| statseason = 2019\n| statweek = \n| statlabel1 = Passing attempts\n| statvalue1 = 10,161\n| statlabel2 = Passing completions\n| statvalue2 = 6,867\n| statlabel3 = Completion percentage \n| statvalue3 = 67.6\n| statlabel4 = Passing yards\n| statvalue4 = 77,416\n| statlabel5 = [[Touchdowns|TD]]\u2013[[Interceptions|INT]]\n| statvalue5 = 547\u2013237\n| statlabel6 = [[Passer rating]]\n| statvalue6 = 98.4\n| nfl = 2504775\n| pfr = BreeDr00\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Christopher Brees''' ({{IPAc-en|b|r|i\u02d0|z}};<ref>{{Cite news |title=News at 10 P.M. |date=November 3, 2009 |publisher=[[WWL-TV]] |quote=Drew also told Juan [Kincaid] that the correct pronunciation of his last name is \"breece\", not \"breeze\". He says the mispronunciation caught on in middle school, and rather than fight it he just went with it.}}</ref> born January 15, 1979) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] for the [[New Orleans Saints]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He had a successful [[college football]] career at [[Purdue University]], becoming one of the most decorated players in [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Purdue]] and [[Big Ten Conference]] history. Brees set two NCAA records, 13 Big Ten Conference records, and 19 Purdue University records during his college career. He remains the Big Ten record-holder in several passing categories, including completions (1,026), attempts (1,678), and yards (11,792). Brees was chosen by the [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]] with the first pick in the second round of the [[2001 NFL Draft]]. Brees earned the starting job with the Chargers in 2002 and made the [[Pro Bowl]] in 2004. Nine months after suffering a dislocation in his right shoulder joint and a tear of the labrum and [[rotator cuff]], Brees signed with the Saints as a free agent in 2006. He experienced immediate success in New Orleans, leading the Saints to their first-ever [[Super Bowl]] in [[Super Bowl XLIV]] and helping the team to a 31\u201317 victory over the [[Indianapolis Colts]].\n\nSince joining the Saints, Brees has led all NFL quarterbacks in touchdowns, passing yards, and 300-yard games. Brees holds NFL records for [[List of National Football League career passing completions leaders|career pass completions]], [[List of National Football League career passing completions leaders|career completion percentage]], [[List of National Football League passing yards leaders|career passing yards]], and [[List of National Football League career passing touchdowns leaders|career touchdown passes]]. He is also second in regular season career pass attempts, third in regular season [[NFL career passer rating leaders|career passer rating]] and fourth in postseason [[NFL career passer rating leaders|career passer rating]]. In 2012, he broke [[Johnny Unitas]]' long-standing record of consecutive games with a touchdown pass. He has led the NFL in passing yards a record seven times and in passing touchdowns a record-tying four times. Brees has made the Pro Bowl 13 times, was the NFL's [[NFL Comeback Player of the Year Award|Comeback Player of the Year]] in 2004, was the [[National Football League Offensive Player of the Year Award|Offensive Player of the Year]] in 2008 and 2011, and was the [[Super Bowl MVP|MVP]] of Super Bowl XLIV. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' named Brees its 2010 [[Sportsman of the Year]]. Brees is regarded as one of the best pure passers in the NFL's history, and has been hailed as one of the greatest quarterbacks of all time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theringer.com/nfl/2018/10/9/17956106/drew-brees-career-passing-yards-record-qb-greatness |title=The Case for Drew Brees As the Quarterback GOAT |last=Sherman |first=Rodger |date=October 9, 2018 |website=The Ringer |access-date=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and high school==\nAndrew Christopher Brees was born on January 15, 1979 in [[Dallas]] to Eugene Wilson \"Chip\" Brees II, a prominent trial lawyer, and Mina Ruth (n\u00e9e Akins; died 2009), an attorney. His grandfather fought in the [[Battle of Okinawa]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sportsday.dallasnews.com/dallas-cowboys/cowboysheadlines/2012/12/19/former-cowboys-fan-drew-brees-has-extra-motivation-this-week |title=Former Cowboys fan Drew Brees has 'extra motivation' this week |last=Machota |first=Jon |date=December 19, 2012 |website=SportsDay |access-date=February 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nola.com/sports/saints/article_d0453acc-2327-5778-947f-246beed7b40c.html |title='He taught me so much': Drew Brees remembers his grandfather, legendary Texas coach Ray Akins |last=Erickson |first=Joel A. |date=December 27, 2017 |website=NOLA.com |language=en |access-date=August 2, 2019}}</ref> A ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' article stated he was named for [[Dallas Cowboys]] wide receiver [[Drew Pearson (American football)|Drew Pearson]]<ref name=\"SI1999\">{{Cite journal |last=Layden |first=Tim |date=August 16, 1999 |title=Drew Brees: About Face |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1016599/index.htm |journal=Sports Illustrated |volume=91 |issue=6 |pages=62\u201368 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091205172531/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1016599/index.htm |archive-date=December 5, 2009}}</ref> but in a 2014 interview Brees said this story was \"just legend\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nola.com/saints/2014/12/drew_brees_tells_show_reports.html |title=Drew Brees says reports about the Saints replacing him have 'absolutely no validity' |last=Morale |first=Amos |date=December 2, 2014 |website=NOLA.com |language=en-US |access-date=February 20, 2019}}</ref> He has a younger brother, Reid (born 1981). When Brees was seven, his parents divorced and shared custody of the boys, who split their time between both parents' homes. Today, he admits that it was a very tough and challenging life after the divorce; however, Brees and his younger brother, Reid, supported each other and became very close.<ref name=\"LaydenT\">{{Cite journal |last=Layden |first=Tim |date=2010 |title=Sportsman of the Year |url=http://eds.a.ebscohost.com.libezp.lib.lsu.edu/eds/detail/detail?sid=dbdc2be9-d3f6-49f3-9e9f-3ea02e0ef526%40sessionmgr4003&vid=0&hid=4205&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWRzLWxpdmUmc2NvcGU9c2l0ZQ%3d%3d#db=s3h&AN=55559667 |journal=Sports Illustrated |volume=113 |issue=21 |page=56}}</ref> They have a younger half-sister, Audrey, from their father's remarriage to Amy Hightower, daughter of the late U.S. Representative ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[Texas|TX]]) [[Jack English Hightower]].<ref name=\"SI2010\">{{Cite magazine |last=Layden |first=Tim |date=December 6, 2010 |title=Sportsman Of The Year Drew Brees |url=https://www.si.com/vault/2010/12/06/106012891/sportsman-of-the-year-drew-brees |magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]]}}</ref><ref name=\"TXMonthly\">{{Cite magazine |date=January 2003 |title=The Joy of Sacks |url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/story/joy-sacks |magazine=[[Texas Monthly]]}}</ref>\n\nBoth of Brees' parents had athletic backgrounds. His father played basketball for the [[Texas A&M Aggies men's basketball|Texas A&M Aggies men's basketball team]], and his mother was a former all-state in three sports in high school.<ref name=\"purdue1999\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/042599aaa.html |title=Focused and Having Fun, Drew Brees Tries to Keep Dreams in Check |last=Huppke |first=Rex W. |date=April 24, 1999 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819102819/http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/042599aaa.html |archive-date=August 19, 2014 |publisher=[[Purdue Boilermakers|Purdue University Athletics]]}}</ref> His maternal uncle, [[Marty Akins]], was an All-American starting quarterback for the [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas Longhorns]] college football team from 1975 to 1977<ref name=\"TXMonthly\" /><ref name=\"ABC2010\" /> and his maternal grandfather, Ray Akins, had the third-most victories as a Texas high school football coach in his three decades at [[Gregory-Portland High School]].<ref name=\"Saints\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2012/12/like_grandfather_like_son_drew.html |title=Drew Brees' greatest influence might be his grandfather, Ray Akins |last=Duncan |first=Jeff |date=December 22, 2012 |work=The Times-Picayune |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121223154544/http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2012/12/like_grandfather_like_son_drew.html |archive-date=December 23, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Duncan |first=Jeff |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2010/02/drew_brees_the_athlete_deserve.html |title=Drew Brees the athlete deserves credit |date=February 2, 2010 |work=[[The Times-Picayune]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206130742/http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2010/02/drew_brees_the_athlete_deserve.html |archive-date=February 6, 2010}}</ref> His younger brother, Reid, was an [[outfielder]] for the [[Baylor Bears baseball|Baylor Bears baseball team]], which made the [[2005 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament#College World Series|2005 College World Series]] and now resides in [[Colorado]], where he works in sales.<ref name=\"ABC2010\">{{Cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Books/excerpt-coming-back-stronger-drew-brees/story?id=11090457&singlePage=true |title=Drew Brees Book Excerpt: 'Coming Back Stronger' |date=July 6, 2010 |publisher=[[ABC News]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.baylorbears.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/brees_reid00.html |title=Reid Brees Biography |publisher=[[Baylor Bears|Baylor Bears Athletics]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810161551/http://www.baylorbears.com/sports/m-basebl/mtt/brees_reid00.html |archive-date=August 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBrees did not play tackle football until high school and was on the [[flag football]] team at [[St. Andrew's Episcopal School (Texas)|St. Andrew's Episcopal School]], where his teammates included actor [[Ben McKenzie]], who was in the same year. In high school, he was a [[varsity letter]]man in baseball, basketball and football<ref name=\"NYTimes\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/02/06/sports/football/06brees.html |title=Brees's Colleagues See an Amazing Athlete Within |last=Bishop |first=Greg |date=February 5, 2010 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref> and was considering playing [[college baseball]] rather than football.<ref name=\"BaltimoreSun\">{{Cite news |url=http://articles.baltimoresun.com/2000-09-01/sports/0009010276_1_drew-brees-tiller-heisman-trophy |title='Cool Brees' is hot commodity |last=McMullen |first=Paul |date=September 1, 2000 |work=[[The Baltimore Sun]] |access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref> College recruiters quickly ran after Brees blew out his knee in the 11th grade.<ref name=LaydenT /> After overcoming an [[Anterior cruciate ligament injury|ACL tear]] during his junior year he was selected as Texas High School 5A Most Valuable Offensive Player in 1996 and led the [[Westlake High School (Austin, Texas)|Westlake High School]] football team to 16\u20130 record and state championship.<ref name=\"TXMonthly\" /><ref name=\"NFL.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/players/profile?id=BRE229498 |title=Drew Brees |website=NFL.com |access-date=January 2, 2011}}</ref> As a high school football player, Brees completed 314 of 490 passes (64.1 percent) for 5,461 yards with 50 touchdowns including, in his senior season, 211 of 333 passes (63.4 percent) for 3,528 yards with 31 touchdowns.<ref name=\"Purdue\" /> Westlake went 28\u20130\u20131 when Brees started for two seasons and beat a [[Dominic Rhodes]]-led [[Cooper High School (Abilene, Texas)|Abilene Cooper]] 55\u201315 in the 1996 title game.<ref name=\"Saints\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.neworleanssaints.com/team/roster/Drew-Brees/09634fe8-9ab7-4f47-a5ea-c0fb5ad343a9 |title=Drew Brees |publisher=New Orleans Saints |access-date=January 2, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Purdue\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/brees_drew00.html |title=Drew Brees Profile - Purdue |publisher=[[Purdue Boilermakers|Purdue University Athletics]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411190603/http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/brees_drew00.html |archive-date=April 11, 2018 |access-date=January 2, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"UIL\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.uiltexas.org/football/archives/P144 |title=Football State Archive |website=University Interscholastic League |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181210203423/http://www.uiltexas.org/football/archives/P144 |archive-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> He was given honorable mention in the state high school all-star football team and the ''[[USA Today]]'' [[USA Today All-USA high school football team|All-USA high school football team]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/football/sfhs96st.htm |title=All-USA high school football |date=January 9, 1997 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref> alongside former [[San Diego Chargers]] teammate and long-time friend [[LaDainian Tomlinson]].<ref name=\"SI2010\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://thsca.pointstreaksites.com/files/uploaded_documents/386/AS-FB_6.pdf |title=Football All-Stars |publisher=Texas High School Coaches Association}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/a-football-life/0ap2000000237948/A-Football-Life-The-LT-and-Brees-connection |title='A Football Life': The LT and Brees connection |date=September 3, 2013 |publisher=[[National Football League|NFL]] |access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref> Brees had hoped to follow his father and uncle's footsteps and play for the [[Texas Longhorns]] or [[Texas A&M Aggies]] but was not heavily recruited despite his stellar record.<ref name=\"TXMonthly\" /><ref name=\"statesman2013\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.statesman.com/news/sports/football/bohls-brees-left-home-but-made-it-proud/nWSt6/ |title=Bohls: Brees left home, but made it proud |last=Bohls |first=Kirk |date=February 19, 2013 |work=[[Austin American-Statesman]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130223024602/https://www.statesman.com/news/sports/football/bohls-brees-left-home-but-made-it-proud/nWSt6/ |archive-date=February 23, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nBrees received offers from only two colleges, [[Purdue University|Purdue]] and [[University of Kentucky|Kentucky]], choosing Purdue for its highly rated academics.<ref name=\"purdue1999\" /> He graduated in 2001 with a degree in [[industrial management]],<ref>{{Cite journal |date=Fall 2010 |title=Game Manager |url=http://www.krannert.purdue.edu/konline/2010f/brees.asp |journal=Krannert Magazine (K-Online) |publisher=[[Purdue University|Purdue]] \u2014 [[Krannert School of Management]] |volume=11 |issue=2}}</ref> and is a member of the [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thesighouse.com/visitors/introToDeltaDelta.html |title=Delta Delta Chapter of Sigma Chi Fraternity |publisher=thesighouse.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119035849/http://www.thesighouse.com/visitors/introToDeltaDelta.html |archive-date=January 19, 2015 |access-date=January 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter a relatively uneventful freshman season, Brees was given his first start during his sophomore year by [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Boilermakers]] head coach [[Joe Tiller]] and became an integral part of Tiller and [[Jim Chaney]]'s unorthodox \"basketball on grass\" [[spread offense]], serving as offensive captain during his junior and senior years.<ref name=\"Tiller\" /><ref name=\"bio\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.drewbrees.com/bio |title=Drew's Bio |publisher=DrewBrees.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110103012109/http://www.drewbrees.com/bio |archive-date=January 3, 2011 |access-date=January 2, 2011}}</ref> He had the option to make himself available for the [[2000 NFL Draft]] but chose to return for his senior year to complete his studies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/vault/2001/04/30/8095409/hang-time-with-his-future-up-in-the-air-purdues-drew-brees-like-many-top-prospects-lived-in-a-maddening-limbo-from-new-years-to-draft-day-working-out-for-nfl-teams-watching-his-draft-status-rise-and-fall-never-knowing-which-pro |title=Drew Brees |last=Layden |first=Tim |date=April 30, 2001 |website=SI Vault |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> In [[2000 NCAA Division I-A football season|2000]], he led the [[Purdue Boilermakers football|Boilermakers]] to memorable last-minute upsets against top-ranked [[2000 Ohio State Buckeyes football team|Ohio State]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/scores100/100302/100302383.htm |title=NCAA Football \u2013 Ohio State vs. Purdue |date=October 28, 2000 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> and [[2000 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]] en route to the Boilermakers' first [[List of Big Ten Conference football champions|Big Ten championship]] (shared with [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]] and [[Northwestern Wildcats football|Northwestern]]) since 1967.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/conferences/big-ten/ |title=Big Ten Conference Index |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> The Ohio State game was replayed on [[ESPN Classic]] and is widely remembered for Brees' four [[interception]]s and 64-yard touchdown pass to Seth Morales with 1:55 remaining to seal a vital 31\u201327 win, prompting commentator [[Brent Musburger]] to exclaim \"Holy Toledo!\" and a post-game [[Pitch invasion|field rush]] afterwards.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/102813aab.html |title=Football Game Notes \u2013 vs. No. 4 Ohio State |date=October 28, 2013 |access-date=August 18, 2019 |publisher=[[Purdue Boilermakers|Purdue University Athletics]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hammerandrails.com/2008/05/best-wins-of-tiller-era-1-ohio-state.html |title=Best Wins of the Tiller Era #1 Ohio State 2000 |last=Miller |first=Travis |date=May 27, 2008 |website=Hammer & Rails |publisher=[[SB Nation]] |access-date=December 4, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.utsandiego.com/sports/chargers/20020908-9999_1s8chargers.html |title=Mr. Cool \u2014 Quarterback Brees has a knack for coming through in the clutch |last=Trotter |first=Jim |date=September 8, 2002 |work=[[U-T San Diego]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430093909/http://www.utsandiego.com/sports/chargers/20020908-9999_1s8chargers.html |archive-date=April 30, 2015}}</ref> Due to head-to-head victories over Michigan and Northwestern, Purdue won the invitation to the [[2001 Rose Bowl]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://a.espncdn.com/ncf/2000/20001118/recap/iieppj.html |title=Purdue wins share of Big Ten title |date=November 18, 2000 |access-date=August 18, 2019 |publisher=[[ESPN]] |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Purdue's first appearance there since 1967, where Purdue lost by ten points to the [[2000 Washington Huskies football team|Washington Huskies]].\n\nBrees was a finalist for the [[Davey O'Brien Award]] as the nation's best quarterback in 1999.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://daveyobrienaward.org/year-by-year-finalists/ |title=Year-by-Year Finalists |website=Davey O'Brien Foundation |language=en-US |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He won the [[Maxwell Award]] as the nation's outstanding player of 2000<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.maxwellfootballclub.org/award-winner/drew-brees |title=Maxwell Award Winner \u2013 Drew Brees |work=Maxwell Football Club |access-date=August 18, 2019 |publisher=[[Maxwell Football Club]]}}</ref> and the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]'s [[Today's Top 10 Award|Today's Top VIII Award]] as a member of the Class of 2001.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/NCAANewsArchive/2000/association-wide/2001%2Btoday_s%2Btop%2Bviii%2Breflect%2Bstudent-athlete%2Bleadership%2B-%2B12-18-00.html |title=2001 Today's Top VIII reflect student-athlete leadership |date=December 18, 2000 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812204713/http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/NCAANewsArchive/2000/association-wide/2001%2Btoday_s%2Btop%2Bviii%2Breflect%2Bstudent-athlete%2Bleadership%2B-%2B12-18-00.html |archive-date=August 12, 2014 |publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]}}</ref> Brees was also fourth in [[Heisman Trophy]] voting in 1999 and third in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/awards/heisman-1999.html |title=1999 Heisman Trophy Voting |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> As a senior, Brees became the first Boilermaker since Bruce Brineman in 1989 to earn [[List of Football Academic All-America Team Members of the Year|Academic All-America]] honors.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.purduesports.com/trads/all-americans.html |title=First Team All-Americans |publisher=[[Purdue Boilermakers|Purdue University Athletics]] |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180501103555/http://www.purduesports.com/trads/all-americans.html |archive-date=May 1, 2018 |access-date=August 10, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"grad2001\" /><ref>{{Cite magazine |date=September 5, 2013 |title=Drew Brees |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/photos/2013/09/05/drew-brees-classic-photos# |magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924042524/http://www.si.com/nfl/photos/2013/09/05/drew-brees-classic-photos |archive-date=September 24, 2014 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/NCAANewsArchive/2000/association-wide/purdue_s+brees+heads+2000+football+academic+all-americans+-+12-18-00.html |title=Purdue's Brees heads 2000 football Academic All-Americans |date=December 18, 2000 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924042724/http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/NCAANewsArchive/2000/association-wide/purdue_s+brees+heads+2000+football+academic+all-americans+-+12-18-00.html |archive-date=September 24, 2014 |publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]]}}</ref> Additionally, he won Academic All-Big Ten honors a record three times,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/pur/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/sg07-sect02.pdf |title=Media Guide \u2013 Academic All-Big Ten Honorees |date=2007 |publisher=[[Purdue Boilermakers|Purdue University Athletics]] |page=51}}</ref> was initiated into [[Mortar Board]]<ref name=\"grad2001\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.purdue.edu/uns/html3month/2001/010427.Graduation.briefs.html |title=Purdue Graduation Briefs \u2013 Brees throws touchdowns in game of life |date=April 27, 2001 |access-date=August 18, 2019 |publisher=[[Purdue University|purdue.edu]]}}</ref> and awarded the [[Big Ten Medal of Honor]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://grfx.cstv.com/photos/schools/big10/genrel/auto_pdf/2013-14/misc_non_event/2013-14MedalofHonor.pdf |title=Conference Medal of Honor Winners |website=CSTV.com |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> and the [[National Football Foundation|NFF]] National Scholar-Athlete Award.<ref name=\"NFF\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.footballfoundation.org/News/NewsDetail/tabid/567/Article/52407/three-nff-scholar-athletes-picked-in-nfl-draft.aspx |title=Three NFF Scholar-Athletes Picked In NFL Draft |date=April 27, 2001 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812205622/http://www.footballfoundation.org/News/NewsDetail/tabid/567/Article/52407/three-nff-scholar-athletes-picked-in-nfl-draft.aspx |archive-date=August 12, 2014 |publisher=[[National Football Foundation]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/110100aab.html |title=Brees Named National College Scholar-Athlete |date=November 1, 2000 |access-date=August 18, 2019 |publisher=[[Purdue Boilermakers|Purdue University Athletics]]}}</ref> Brees also was awarded Purdue's Leonard Wilson Award for unselfishness and dedication.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://purduesports.com/news/2000/11/20/Brees_Named_Football_Most_Valuable_Player.aspx |title=Brees Named Football Most Valuable Player |date=November 20, 2000 |website=Purdue University Athletics |language=en |access-date=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn his college career, Brees set two NCAA records, 13 [[Big Ten Conference]] records, and 19 Purdue University records.<ref name=\"purduesports.com\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/083010aaa.html |title=Week 1 Cradle Of Quarterbacks Feature: Drew Brees, 1997\u20132000 |date=August 30, 2010 |access-date=August 18, 2019 |publisher=[[Purdue Boilermakers|Purdue University Athletics]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161210130053/http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/083010aaa.html |archive-date=December 10, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He left Purdue with Big Ten Conference records in passing yards (11,792),<ref name=\"NYTimes\" /> [[touchdown]] passes (90), total offensive yards (12,693), completions (1,026), and attempts (1,678).<ref name=\"Tiller\">{{Cite news |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/college/football/2008-09-24-572669948_x.htm |title=Purdue coach Tiller's spread offense leaves mark |last=Brunt |first=Cliff |date=September 24, 2008 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He tied an NCAA record with the 99-yard pass to receiver [[Vinny Sutherland]] against [[1999 Northwestern Wildcats football team|Northwestern]] on September 25, 1999 and held the NCAA record for pass attempts in a game (83) for 15 years, until [[2013 Washington State Cougars football team|Washington State]] quarterback [[Connor Halliday]] broke it in October 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/ncf/s/heisman/0925.html |title=Heisman Watch '99 |date=September 25, 1999 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sportingnews.com/us/ncaa-football/news/ncaa-passing-record-89-passes-connor-halliday-drew-brees/obe5c7355a4kzultmle2n8nc |title=Connor Halliday breaks Drew Brees' record with 89 pass attempts |date=October 20, 2013 |website=www.sportingnews.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Brees was inducted into Purdue's Intercollegiate Athletics Hall of Fame.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.purduesports.com/school-bio/pur-hallfame.html |title=Purdue Intercollegiate Athletics Hall Of Fame |website=www.purduesports.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130423073252/http://www.purduesports.com/school-bio/pur-hallfame.html |archive-date=April 23, 2013 |access-date=May 9, 2013}}</ref> The [[Big Ten Conference]]'s [[Big Ten Conference football individual awards#Griese\u2013Brees Quarterback of the Year|Griese\u2013Brees Quarterback of the Year]] award initiated in 2011 was named in his and [[Bob Griese]]'s honor.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.purdueexponent.org/sports/article_6c646d9e-06ef-11e0-9af0-00127992bc8b.html |title=Griese, Brees, Woodson will have Big Ten awards in their names |date=December 13, 2010 |website=Purdue Exponent |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He was named the Big Ten's best quarterback of the 1990s<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://btn.com/video/315254851594/ |title=Drew Brees \u2013 1990s Best Quarterbacks |publisher=[[Big Ten Network]] |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> and ranked number 48 on the 2010 documentary ''[[Big Ten Icons]]'', featuring the conference's top fifty student-athletes.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/090310aab.html |title='Big Ten Icons' Countdown Continues With Brees |date=September 3, 2010 |access-date=August 18, 2019 |publisher=[[Purdue Boilermakers|Purdue University Athletics]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.bigten.org/genrel/030410aaa.html |title='Big Ten Icons' to Count Down Conference's All-Time Top 50 Student-Athletes |date=March 4, 2010 |access-date=August 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029190235/http://www.bigten.org/genrel/030410aaa.html |archive-date=October 29, 2013 |publisher=[[Big Ten Conference]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bigtenicons.com/openlocker.cfm?id=48&name=DREW-BREES |title=Big Ten Icons \u2013 Drew Brees |publisher=[[Big Ten Icons|bigtenicons.com]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100907092229/http://www.bigtenicons.com/openlocker.cfm?id=48&name=DREW-BREES |archive-date=September 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=3| !! colspan=\"6\"|Passing\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! GP !! Cmp !! Att !! Pct !! Yds !! TD !! Int \n|-\n! [[1997 NCAA Division I-A football season|1997]] !! [[1997 Purdue Boilermakers football team|Purdue]]\n| 8 || 19 || 43 || 44.2 || 232 || 0 || 1\n|-\n! [[1998 NCAA Division I-A football season|1998]] !! [[1998 Purdue Boilermakers football team|Purdue]]\n| 13 || 361 || 569 || 63.4 || 3,983 || 39 || 20 \n|-\n! [[1999 NCAA Division I-A football season|1999]] !! [[1999 Purdue Boilermakers football team|Purdue]]\n| 12 || 337 || 554 || 60.8 || 3,909 || 25 || 12\n|-\n! [[2000 NCAA Division I-A football season|2000]] !! [[2000 Purdue Boilermakers football team|Purdue]]\n| 12 || 309 || 512 || 60.4 || 3,668 || 26 || 12\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total !! 45 !! 1,026 !! 1,678 !! 61.1 !! 11,792 !! 90 !! 45\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n{{nfl predraft\n| height ft = 6\n| height in = 0\u00bc\n| weight = 213\n| dash = 4.83\n| ten split = 1.66\n| twenty split = 2.75\n| shuttle = 4.21\n| cone drill = 7.09\n| vertical = 32\n| broad ft = 8\n| broad in = 9\n| bench = \n| wonderlic = 28\n| arm span = 31\n| hand span = 10\u00bc\n| note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Draft Scout 2001 QB Player Ratings |url=http://www.draftscout.com/players.php?GenPos=QB&DraftYear=2001&sortorder=TSXPos&order=ASC |website=www.draftscout.com |accessdate=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===San Diego Chargers (2001\u20132005)===\n====2001 NFL Draft====\nBrees' college success led to projections that he would be a mid\u2013late first-round draft pick in the [[2001 NFL Draft]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/melkiper/s/2001/0305/1130313.html |title=Kiper's first-round draft projection |last=Kiper |first=Mel |date=March 29, 2001 |access-date=August 18, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180316023734/http://www.espn.com/melkiper/s/2001/0305/1130313.html |archive-date=March 16, 2018 |publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> but he slipped due to concerns about his relatively short stature for a professional quarterback (6'), a perceived lack of arm strength, and a sense that he had succeeded in college in a spread offense. Brees was the second quarterback, behind [[Michael Vick]] of [[Virginia Tech Hokies football|Virginia Tech]], selected in the 2001 Draft, chosen by the [[San Diego Chargers]] as the first pick of the second round and 32nd overall.<ref name=\"AP2001\">{{Cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/nfl/2001/draft/news/2001/04/21/chargers_draft_ap |title=Trade works well as Chargers get Tomlinson, then Brees |date=April 21, 2001 |work=[[Associated Press|AP]] at [[Sports Illustrated]] |access-date=January 19, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010428081128/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/nfl/2001/draft/news/2001/04/21/chargers_draft_ap/ |archive-date=April 28, 2001}}</ref> San Diego originally had the first pick in that draft, but traded it to [[Atlanta Falcons|Atlanta]] (who drafted Vick) in return for the fifth pick of the first round; which San Diego drafted [[LaDainian Tomlinson]].<ref name=\"AP2001\" />\n\n====Early career====\n{{See also|2001 San Diego Chargers season|2002 San Diego Chargers season|2003 San Diego Chargers season}}\nIn his rookie season, Brees was the backup quarterback to [[Doug Flutie]], who started all 16 games that season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/sdg/2001.htm |title=2001 San Diego Chargers Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> Brees played in his first professional game on November 4, 2001 against the [[2001 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]] in Week 8. He came into the game to relieve Flutie, who had suffered a concussion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://chiefswire.usatoday.com/2016/10/20/throwback-thursday-chiefs-defeated-drew-brees-in-his-1st-career-game/ |title=Throwback Thursday: Chiefs defeated Drew Brees in his 1st career game |date=October 20, 2016 |website=Chiefs Wire |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He finished with 221 passing yards and his first career passing touchdown, a 20-yard pass to [[Freddie Jones (American football)|Freddie Jones]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200111040sdg.htm |title=Kansas City Chiefs at San Diego Chargers \u2013 November 4th, 2001 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> The game against the Chiefs was Brees's lone appearance as a rookie.\n\nOn August 19, 2002, he was named the starter for the [[2002 NFL season|2002 season]] over Doug Flutie.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/2002/08/19/Brees-named-Chargers-starting-QB/9221029729600/ |title=Brees named Chargers' starting QB |date=August 19, 2002 |publisher=[[United Press International]] |access-date=December 8, 2017}}</ref> Brees started all 16 games for the Chargers. The season started off well for the Chargers with a 6\u20131 start, but faded down the stretch with a 2\u20137 record over the last nine games to finish 8\u20138.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/sdg/2002.htm |title=2002 San Diego Chargers Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He finished the 2002 season with 3,284 passing yards, 17 touchdowns, and 16 interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BreeDr00/gamelog/2002 |title=Drew Brees 2002 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 4 of the 2003 season, Brees recorded a 21-yard touchdown reception on a pass thrown by LaDainian Tomlinson in the 34\u201331 overtime loss to the [[2003 Oakland Raiders|Oakland Raiders]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-2003-09-29-0309290341-story.html |title=OT Victory has Raiders on Upswing |website=OrlandoSentinel.com |language=en-US |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref> After a disappointing 1\u20137 start to the [[2003 NFL season|2003 season]], Brees was replaced by Flutie, though he regained the job by Week 15.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/blog/new-orleans-saints/post/_/id/19507 |title=Drew Brees recalls game that saved his job, catapulted career |date=November 20, 2015 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=August 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/sdg/2003.htm |title=2003 San Diego Chargers Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> In 11 games, he finished with 2,108 passing yards, 11 touchdowns, and 15 interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BreeDr00/gamelog/2003 |title=Drew Brees 2003 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2004 season====\n{{See also|2004 San Diego Chargers season}}\nBrees' career with the Chargers was in jeopardy after San Diego [[2004 NFL Draft#Notes|acquired]] [[North Carolina State Wolfpack football|NC State's]] [[Philip Rivers]] after the [[2004 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2004/draft.htm |title=2004 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref> With a looming quarterback controversy, he performed well through training camp and the preseason, while Rivers held out during training camp, essentially guaranteeing him the job to begin the season with Rivers as his backup.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.star-telegram.com/sports/nfl/article223379285.html |title=Looking Back: When the Chargers had two MVP caliber quarterbacks on their roster |last=Engel |first=Mac |website=Fort Worth Star-Telegram |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBrees remained the starter throughout the [[2004 NFL season|2004 season]], where he started 15 games and led the team to a 12\u20134 regular season record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/sdg/2004.htm |title=2004 San Diego Chargers Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref> In Week 8, against the [[2004 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], he was 22 of 25 for 281 yards and five touchdowns in the 42\u201314 victory to earn his first AFC Offensive Player of the Week honor.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200410310sdg.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at San Diego Chargers \u2013 October 31st, 2004 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2004/week_8.htm |title=2004 NFL Week 8 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> Brees posted spectacular numbers, completing 65.5% of his passes for 3,159 yards, with 27 touchdowns to only seven interceptions, giving him a 104.8 [[passer rating]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BreeDr00/gamelog/2004 |title=Drew Brees 2004 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> The Chargers won the [[AFC West]] for the first time in 10 seasons and Brees was selected to the [[2004 Pro Bowl]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.utsandiego.com/sports/chargers/20050107-9999-1s7chargers.html |title=Once maligned, now divine |last=Acee |first=Kevin |date=January 7, 2005 |work=San Diego Union-Tribune |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306111437/http://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/sports/chargers/20050107-9999-1s7chargers.html |archive-date=March 6, 2016 |publisher=[[U-T San Diego]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2004/probowl.htm |title=2004 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> He was named 2004 [[NFL Comeback Player of the Year]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=1960406 |title=What a comeback: Brees runs away with award |date=January 6, 2005 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2004\u201305 NFL playoffs#AFC: New York Jets 20, San Diego Chargers 17 (OT)|Wild Card Round]] against the [[2004 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], Brees had 319 passing yards, two passing touchdowns, and one interception in the 20\u201317 overtime loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200501080sdg.htm |title=Wild Card - New York Jets at San Diego Chargers - January 8th, 2005 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2005 season====\n{{See also|2005 San Diego Chargers season}}\nBrees became a free agent after the 2004 season and was not expected to return to San Diego, which had already committed a large sum of money to Rivers. The team eventually designated Brees a [[franchise tag|franchise player]], giving him a one-year contract that quadrupled his pay to $8 million for [[2005 NFL season|2005]]. Under the terms of the franchise player contract, Brees was eligible to be traded or to sign with another team, but the Chargers would receive two future first round draft choices in return. He was not traded and continued as the starting quarterback for the remainder of the 2005 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.chargers.com/team/roster/Drew-Brees/BRE229498 |title=San Diego Chargers \u2013 Players |publisher=The San Diego Chargers |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104205946/http://www.chargers.com/team/roster/Drew-Brees/BRE229498 |archive-date=November 4, 2013 |access-date=August 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter a 1\u20132 start, Brees helped lead a 41\u201317 victory over the [[2005 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]]. He was 19 of 24 for 248 passing yards and two touchdowns and earned AFC Offensive Player of the Week for the effort.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200510020nwe.htm |title=San Diego Chargers at New England Patriots \u2013 October 2nd, 2005 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2005/week_4.htm |title=2005 NFL Week 4 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> He posted a career-high in passing yards with 3,576. Brees also posted an 89.2 rating, 10th best in the NFL.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BreeDr00/gamelog/2005 |title=Drew Brees 2005 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2005/passing.htm |title=2005 NFL Passing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> However, in the last game of the 2005 season against the [[2005 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]], Brees tore his [[Glenoidal labrum|labrum]] while trying to pick up his own fumble after being hit by Broncos [[Safety (American football position)|safety]] [[John Lynch (American football)|John Lynch]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2278077 |title=Brees suffers torn labrum, faces four-month rehab |date=January 2, 2006 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> Denver tackle [[Gerard Warren]] hit Brees while he was on the ground, causing the injury.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2010/02/02/brees-like-new-orleans-had-to-start-over/ |title=Brees, like New Orleans, had to start over |last=Vaccaro |first=Mike |date=February 2, 2010 |website=New York Post |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> Brees underwent [[arthroscopic surgery]], performed by [[James Andrews (physician)|Dr. James Andrews]], to repair the torn [[Glenoidal labrum|labrum]] in his right (throwing) shoulder on January 5, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/si-wire/2014/06/13/james-andrews-drew-brees-remarkable-comeback |title=Dr. James Andrews on Drew Brees: 'Most remarkable comeback that I've ever treated' |website=SI.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> Subsequent reports mentioned additional [[rotator cuff]] damage and he also was treated by Dr. Saby Szajowitz to recover and regain muscle movement.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.neworleanssaints.dk/drew-brees-the-american-version/ |title=Drew Brees' profile \u2013 The American version |date=August 25, 2011 |website=NewOrleansSaints.dk |language=da-DK |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter the season, the Chargers offered Brees a five-year, $50 million contract that paid $2 million in base salary the first year and the rest heavily based on performance incentives.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://whodatwarriors.com/2016/02/15/drew-brees-contract-history/ |title=Drew Brees Contract History |date=February 15, 2016 |website=Who Dat Warriors |language=en-US |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===New Orleans Saints (2006\u2013present)===\nAfter the Chargers refused to increase their offer, Brees met with other teams. The [[New Orleans Saints]] and the [[Miami Dolphins]] were interested in Brees. New Orleans made an offer that included $10 million in guaranteed money the first year and a $12 million option the second year. Miami was unsure whether Brees' shoulder was completely healed and doctors suggested the team should not sign him because of the injury.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2018/10/nfl-saints-drew-brees-dolphins-2001-draft-josh-heupel-daunte-culpepper |title=The Dolphins actually passed on Drew Brees twice |date=October 9, 2018 |website=For The Win |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d81e3bc82/article/teams-must-be-kicking-themselves-for-not-drafting-rodgers-?module=HP_cp2 |title=Teams must be kicking themselves for not drafting Rodgers |last=Kirwin |first=Pat |date=February 9, 2011 |website=NFL.com |access-date=February 10, 2011}}</ref> The Dolphins ended negotiations and traded for [[Minnesota Vikings]] quarterback [[Daunte Culpepper]] instead.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2368259 |title=Vikings deal Culpepper to Miami for second-round pick |date=March 14, 2006 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> Brees signed a six-year, $60 million deal with the Saints on March 14, 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2368304 |title=Brees takes money, runs to Saints |date=March 14, 2006 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2006 season====\n{{See also|2006 New Orleans Saints season}}\nBrees had a productive first year with the Saints. The team, under first-year head coach [[Sean Payton]], rebounded from its disastrous [[2005 New Orleans Saints season|2005 season]] (when the team was [[Effect of Hurricane Katrina on the New Orleans Saints|unable to play in New Orleans]] due to the [[Effect of Hurricane Katrina on the Louisiana Superdome|damage]] caused by [[Hurricane Katrina]] and struggled to a 3\u201313 record) to finish with a 10\u20136 regular season record and won the NFC South division title.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nor/2006.htm |title=2006 New Orleans Saints Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> On November 5, in the 31\u201314 victory over the [[2006 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], he had 314 passing yards and three touchdowns to earn his first NFC Offensive Player of the Week honor.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200611050tam.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Tampa Bay Buccaneers \u2013 November 5th, 2006 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2006/week_9.htm |title=2006 NFL Week 9 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> On November 19, in a 31\u201316 victory over the [[2006 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], he threw for a career-high 510 passing yards, two touchdowns, and three interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200611190nor.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at New Orleans Saints \u2013 November 19th, 2006 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref> In Week 14, a 42\u201317 victory over the [[2006 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]], he had 384 passing yards and five touchdowns to earn his second NFC Offensive Player of the Week award in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200612100dal.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Dallas Cowboys \u2013 December 10th, 2006 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2006/week_14.htm |title=2006 NFL Week 14 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> Brees threw a league-leading and franchise record 4,418 passing yards, finished third in the league with 26 touchdown passes and 11 interceptions, and had a 96.2 passer rating.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BreeDr00/gamelog/2006 |title=Drew Brees 2006 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> Brees was named starting quarterback for the NFC in the [[2007 Pro Bowl]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2006/probowl.htm |title=2006 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> and was named as a First-team All-Pro.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2006/allpro.htm |title=2006 NFL All-Pros |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> On January 5, 2007, Brees was named first runner-up behind former teammate Tomlinson for league MVP by the [[Associated Press]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://mvpvoting.wordpress.com/2001-2010/ |title=MVP Winners: 2001-2010 |date=November 2, 2011 |website=NFL MVP Voting |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> Brees and Tomlinson were co-recipients of the [[Walter Payton NFL Man of the Year Award]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d82059f05/article/walter-payton-nfl-man-of-the-year |title=Walter Payton NFL Man of the Year |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=February 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 13, 2007, in his first playoff game for New Orleans, Brees was 20\u2013of\u201332 in passing attempts with one touchdown and no interceptions against the [[2006 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] in the [[2006\u201307 NFL playoffs#NFC: New Orleans Saints 27, Philadelphia Eagles 24|Divisional Round]] at the [[Mercedes-Benz Superdome|Louisiana Superdome]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200701130nor.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 Philadelphia Eagles at New Orleans Saints \u2013 January 13th, 2007 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> The Saints held on to win 27\u201324, and advanced to the franchise's first [[NFC Championship Game]] against the [[Chicago Bears]]. Though he completed 27-of-49 passes for 354 yards against the [[2006 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]], and two touchdowns, Brees committed three costly turnovers, and was penalized for an intentional grounding in the endzone, resulting in a [[Safety (American football score)|safety]], as the Saints lost in the [[2006\u201307 NFL playoffs#NFC Championship: Chicago Bears 39, New Orleans Saints 14|NFC Championship]] by a score of 39\u201314.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/recap;_ylt=AnvlF4Cz0U8fEkX29CykCwE5nYcB?gid=20070121003&prov=ap |title=Bears reach first Super Bowl in 21 years |last=Wilner |first=Barry |date=January 22, 2007 |website=Sports.yahoo.com |access-date=November 28, 2008}}</ref> Brees dislocated his left elbow during the first quarter of the Pro Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2761463 |title=Brees dislocates non-throwing elbow in Pro Bowl |date=February 11, 2007 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=November 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2007 season====\n{{See also|2007 New Orleans Saints season}}\nBrees's second season with the Saints started rough with an 0\u20134 start, with three losses by the Saints in that stretch by at least 17 points.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://oklahoman.com/article/3121845/manning-colts-rout-saints-41-10/ |title=Manning, Colts Rout Saints 41-10 |date=September 7, 2007 |website=Oklahoman.com |language=en-US |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200709160tam.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Tampa Bay Buccaneers - September 16th, 2007 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://tucson.com/sports/football/professional/nfl/this-is-a-tough-one-monday-night-football-titans-saints/article_c535cc03-6470-53b7-9edd-180f588a511b.html |title='This is a tough one': Monday night football: Titans 31, Saints 14 |last=Newberry |first=Paul |website=Arizona Daily Star |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> However, the Saints started a winning streak after Week 5. In Week 8, a 31\u201310 victory over the [[2007 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]], he had 336 passing yards and four touchdowns to earn NFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200710280sfo.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at San Francisco 49ers \u2013 October 28th, 2007 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2007/week_8.htm |title=2007 NFL Week 8 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> After the next game, a 41\u201324 victory over the [[2007 Jacksonville Jaguars|Jacksonville Jaguars]], the Saints were back at .500 with a 4-4 record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://oklahoman.com/article/3164185/saints-get-back-to-500/ |title=Saints Get Back to .500 |date=November 5, 2007 |website=Oklahoman.com |language=en-US |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> In Week 15, a 31\u201324 victory over the [[2007 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]], he had 315 passing yards and two touchdowns to earn another NFC Offensive Player of the Week nod in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200712160nor.htm |title=Arizona Cardinals at New Orleans Saints \u2013 December 16th, 2007 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2007/week_15.htm |title=2007 NFL Week 15 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> Overall, in the [[2007 NFL season|2007 season]], Brees passed for 4,423 yards, topped his own record and tied a then franchise record with 28 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BreeDr00/gamelog/2007 |title=Drew Brees 2007 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> He also set the NFL record previously held by [[Rich Gannon]] for pass completions in a single season with 440.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/pass_cmp_single_season.htm |title=NFL Passes Completed Single-Season Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 20, 2019}}</ref> However, the [[2007 New Orleans Saints season|Saints]] missed the playoffs with a 7\u20139 record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2007/index.htm |title=2007 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2008 season====\n[[File:Drew Brees Saints 2008.jpg|220px|right|thumb|Brees in 2008 in [[Fedex Field|Landover]]]]\n{{See also|2008 New Orleans Saints season}}\nIn [[2008 NFL season|2008]], the Saints again missed the playoffs but Brees had a strong year statistically, finishing 15 yards short of the NFL record for passing yards thrown in a single season set by [[Dan Marino]] in [[1984 NFL Season|1984]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.spokesman.com/stories/2008/dec/29/brees-finishes-15-yards-shy-of-marinos-mark/ |title=Brees finishes 15 yards shy of Marino's mark |website=The Spokesman-Review |access-date=July 23, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 6, a 34\u20133 victory over the [[2008 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]], he was 26 of 30 for 320 yards and three touchdowns to earn NFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200810120nor.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at New Orleans Saints \u2013 October 12th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2008/week_6.htm |title=2008 NFL Week 6 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> In Week 8, a 37\u201332 victory over the [[2008 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]], he had 339 passing yards and three touchdowns to earn another NFC Offensive Player of the Week nod.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200810260nor.htm |title=San Diego Chargers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 October 26th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2008/week_8.htm |title=2008 NFL Week 8 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> In Week 12, a 51\u201329 win over the [[2008 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]], he had 323 passing yards and four touchdowns to earn his third NFC Offensive Player of the Week honor in 2008.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200811240nor.htm |title=Green Bay Packers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 November 24th, 2008 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2008/week_12.htm |title=2008 NFL Week 12 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> He finished the season with 5,069 yards and became the second quarterback in NFL history to throw for over 5,000 yards in a season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BreeDr00/gamelog/2008 |title=Drew Brees 2008 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/pass_yds_single_season.htm |title=NFL Passing Yards Single-Season Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29776&displayPage=tab_recap |title=Kasay helps Panthers solidify NFC's No. 2 seed with win over Saints |date=December 28, 2008 |publisher=Associated Press via NFL.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090306233158/http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/recap?game_id=29776&displayPage=tab_recap |archive-date=March 6, 2009 |access-date=December 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHe passed for 300 yards ten times during the 2008 season, tying [[Rich Gannon]]'s [[2002 NFL Season|2002]] record. He was named [[FedEx Air & Ground NFL Players of the Week|FedEx Air Player of the Week]] for his performances during Weeks 8 and 12 and was named the [[Associated Press|AP]] 2008 Offensive Player of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/705275593/Saints-QB-Brees-is-AP-Offensive-Player-of-Year.html |title=Saints QB Brees is AP Offensive Player of Year |date=January 6, 2009 |website=DeseretNews.com |language=en |access-date=February 20, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> He was named to his third career Pro Bowl for his 2008 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2008/probowl.htm |title=2008 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBrees started to serve on the Executive Committee of the [[National Football League Players Association]] this season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nola.com/sports/saints/article_251f89aa-3107-5ab1-8d99-05b52362e267.html |title=New Orleans Saints quarterback Drew Brees proud of his stand against the NFL |last=Triplett |first=Mike |website=NOLA.com |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> He remained on the committee through the 2014 season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2014/03/18/nflpa-president-ben-watson-ryan-clark-eric-winston/6586737 |title=Three candidates emerge in race for NFLPA president |last=Pelissero |first=Tom |date=March 18, 2014 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/new-orleans-saints/post/_/id/5751/brees-steps-down-from-nflpa-committee |title=Brees steps down from NFLPA committee |last=Pelissero |first=Tom |date=March 19, 2014 |access-date=August 17, 2019 |publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>\n\n====2009 season: Super Bowl XLIV====\n{{See also|2009 New Orleans Saints season}}\nIn the first game of the [[2009 NFL season|2009 season]] against the [[2009 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]], Brees set a career-high and franchise-tying record with six touchdown passes, going 26 out of 34 for 358 yards. He earned NFC Offensive Player of the Week for his performance against the Lions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000606062/printable/brees-saints-kicked-off-historic-season-vs-lions |title=Brees, Saints kicked off historic season vs. Lions |website=NFL.com |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2009/week_1.htm |title=2009 NFL Week 1 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> The next week, Brees led the Saints to a 48\u201322 win over the [[2009 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], throwing for 311 yards and three touchdown passes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200909200phi.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Philadelphia Eagles \u2013 September 20th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> Brees also tied the record for most touchdown passes by the end of Week 2 with nine touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/261037-it-wont-be-a-brees-but-a-billstampede-will-cool-off-the-saints |title=IT WON'T BE A BREES, BUT A BILLSTAMPEDE WILL COOL OFF THE SAINTS |last=Guee |first=Joe |website=Bleacher Report |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> In Week 6 against the 5\u20130 [[2009 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], Brees completed 23 of 30 passes for 369 yards, four touchdown passes, and a passer rating of 156.8 in a dominant 48\u201327 victory to his second NFC Offensive Player of the Week nod of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200910180nor.htm |title=New York Giants at New Orleans Saints \u2013 October 18th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2009/week_6.htm |title=2009 NFL Week 6 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 7, Brees led a dramatic comeback victory on the road against the [[2009 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], 46\u201334. The [[2009 New Orleans Saints season|Saints]] quickly faced a 24\u20133 deficit in the second quarter, trailing for the first time all season at that point, and failing to score on their first possession as they had in all of their previous contests. Brees had a poor outing, but provided two crucial rushing touchdowns, one just before halftime to narrow the deficit to 24\u201310, and one in the third quarter to give the Saints their first lead of the game, 37\u201334.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nola.com/sports/saints/article_569c3e13-b654-567f-81c8-1c0fa3734392.html |title=Saints still perfect after thrilling comeback win over Dolphins |last=Allee-Walsh |first=Brian |website=NOLA.com |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe next week, Brees threw for 308 yards on 25 of 33 passing along with two touchdowns and one interception in leading the Saints to a 35\u201327 victory and franchise tying best start at 7\u20130 against the rival [[2009 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200911020nor.htm |title=Atlanta Falcons at New Orleans Saints \u2013 November 2nd, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> In week 9, Brees helped guide the team to a 30\u201320 victory over the [[2009 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]]. This was Brees's first victory over the Carolina Panthers in the Superdome and gave the Saints their best ever start in franchise history at 8\u20130.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200911080nor.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 November 8th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> In Week 12, Brees led the Saints to an 11\u20130 record, defeating the [[2009 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] 38\u201317 on ''[[Monday Night Football]]''. Brees totaled 371 yards passing, posting a [[perfect passer rating]] of 158.3, and became the first player to throw for five touchdowns against a team coached by [[Bill Belichick]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nola.com/sports/saints/article_31dd4b8e-66c1-5d82-a4ff-0498df421308.html |title=Remembering Patriots-Saints in 2009 when Drew Brees authored the best passing performance in modern NFL history |last=Duncan |first=Jeff |website=NOLA.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He earned his third NFC Offensive Player of the Week nod for the 2009 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200911300nor.htm |title=New England Patriots at New Orleans Saints \u2013 November 30th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2009/week_12.htm |title=2009 NFL Week 12 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> After close victories over the [[2009 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] and Falcons in successive weeks to start 13\u20130, Brees and the Saints lost for the first time that season to the [[2009 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]], 24\u201317, after [[DeMarcus Ware]] caused a Brees fumble in the final seconds, ending a fourth quarter rally.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/200912190nor.htm |title=Dallas Cowboys at New Orleans Saints \u2013 December 19th, 2009 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> The Saints lost their last two games, with Brees sitting out the Week 17 finale against the Carolina Panthers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201001030car.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Carolina Panthers - January 3rd, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> Their 13\u20133 record secured the #1 seed in the NFC.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nor/2009.htm |title=2009 New Orleans Saints Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBrees' individual statistics led to numerous accolades,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.theadvertiser.com/article/20100121/SPORTS/1210325/Savior-Saint |title=Savior Saint |last=Aymond |first=Brady |work=The Advertiser |access-date=May 11, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313134726/http://www.theadvertiser.com/article/20100121/SPORTS/1210325/Savior-Saint |archive-date=March 13, 2012}}</ref> including a [[Pro Bowl]] selection, the [[Maxwell Football Club]]'s [[Bert Bell Award]], and runner-up in voting for the AP [[National Football League Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]], [[National Football League Offensive Player of the Year Award|Offensive Player of the Year]], and [[All-Pro]] awards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2009/probowl.htm |title=2009 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/awards/bert-bell-award.htm |title=Bert Bell Award (Player of the Year) Winners |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> He finished the season with a completion percentage of 70.62, establishing a new NFL record.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/sports/2010656444_apfbnsaintsbreesrecord.html |title=Like Williams, Brees prefers to play for record |last=Martel |first=Brett |date=December 31, 2009 |access-date=January 13, 2010 |publisher=Associated Press in Seattle Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/indiv/passing |title=Record & Fact Book |work=NFL.com |access-date=January 13, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513031657/http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/indiv/passing |archive-date=May 13, 2008 |publisher=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2009\u201310 NFL playoffs#NFC: New Orleans Saints 45, Arizona Cardinals 14|Divisional Round]], Brees recorded 247 passing yards and three touchdowns as the Saints routed the [[2009 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]] 45\u201314. In the [[2009\u201310 NFL playoffs#NFC Championship: New Orleans Saints 31, Minnesota Vikings 28 (OT)|NFC Championship]], The Saints defeated the [[2009 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]] 31\u201328 in overtime. Brees completed 17 of 31 passes for 197 yards and three touchdowns.<ref name=Jenkins /> The Saints defeated the [[2009 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]] 31\u201317 in [[Super Bowl XLIV]] on February 7, 2010. Brees tied a Super Bowl record with 32 pass completions and won the [[Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award]]. He threw for 288 yards and two touchdowns. It was the first league championship in Saints franchise history.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/2010-02-07-super-bowl_N.htm |title=Saints stump Colts 31\u201317 to win franchise's first Super Bowl title |last=Bell |first=Jarrett |date=February 7, 2010 |work=USA Today |access-date=February 8, 2010}}</ref> Brees was named the 2010 ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' Sportsman of the Year, both for his winning the Super Bowl and his charitable work towards the reconstruction of New Orleans.<ref name=\"SOY\">{{Cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/magazine/11/29/sportsman |title=New Orleans Saints' Drew Brees named SI's Sportsman of the Year |last=Layden |first=Tim |date=November 30, 2010 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |access-date=November 30, 2010}}</ref> On December 17, 2010, he was named AP Male Athlete of the Year. Within four short years after joining the Saints, Brees was more accurate in his throws than any of the Saints' past quarterbacks.<ref name=\"Jenkins\">{{Cite journal |last=Jenkins |first=Lee |date=2010 |title=For You, New Orleans |url=http://eds.b.ebscohost.com.libezp.lib.lsu.edu/eds/detail/detail?sid=4759fcd6-676b-4c34-82ac-6a20454fb334%40sessionmgr111&vid=0&hid=119&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWRzLWxpdmUmc2NvcGU9c2l0ZQ%3d%3d#db=s3h&AN=48076924 |journal=Sports Illustrated |volume=112 |issue=7 |page=30 |access-date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> Brees and his teammates were welcomed back to New Orleans with a blues band along with thousands of celebrating fans.<ref name=Jenkins />\n\n[[File:Drew Brees after winning Super Bowl XLIV Jan. 7th, 2010.jpg|thumb|left|Brees celebrating the Super Bowl win with his son Baylen]]\n\n====2010 season====\n{{See also|2010 New Orleans Saints season}}\nBrees started the 2010 season with 237 yards and one passing touchdown in a 14\u20139 win over the [[2010 Minnesota Vikings|Minnesota Vikings]] in a rematch of the previous years' NFC Championship.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009090nor.htm |title=Minnesota Vikings at New Orleans Saints - September 9th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> In Week 3, against the [[2010 Atlanta Falcons|Atlanta Falcons]], he threw for 365 yards, three touchdowns, and two interceptions in a 27\u201324 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201009260nor.htm |title=Atlanta Falcons at New Orleans Saints - September 26th, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> In Week 11, against the [[2010 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]], he threw for a regular season-high 382 yards, four touchdowns, and two interceptions in a 34\u201319 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201011210nor.htm |title=Seattle Seahawks at New Orleans Saints - November 21st, 2010 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> In 2010, the Saints qualified for the playoffs with a 11\u20135 record, but were eliminated in the [[2010\u201311 NFL playoffs#NFC: Seattle Seahawks 41, New Orleans Saints 36|Wild Card Round]] by the Seattle Seahawks by a score of 41\u201336 in the [[Beast Quake]] game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/2014/01/12/lynch-seahawks-run-past-saints-/4434553/ |title=Lynch, Seahawks run past Saints |website=Citizen Times |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> Brees finished with 404 passing yards and two passing touchdowns in the loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201101080sea.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 New Orleans Saints at Seattle Seahawks \u2013 January 8th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> Brees was selected to his fifth Pro Bowl-fourth with the Saints.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/nfl/2010/12/28/1900658/2011-pro-bowl-rosters-announced-nfl-network |title=2011 NFL Pro Bowl: NFC Ties Scoring Record In 55-41 Win |last=Thorman |first=Joel |date=December 28, 2010 |website=SBNation.com |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> Brees had a less successful season statistically, throwing a career-high 22 interceptions, tying the franchise record held by [[Aaron Brooks (American football)|Aaron Brooks]], although he managed to throw 33 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d81edf13e/article/nfl-network-series-ranks-the-100-best-players-of-2011 |title=NFL Network series ranks the 100 best players of 2011 |date=March 21, 2011 |website=NFL.com |access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref> He was ranked ninth on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2011]] players' list.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.neworleanssaints.com/media-center/videos/Top-100-Drew-Brees/82bbf7d9-60e3-4048-8aab-2a3610c676f1 |title=Top 100: Drew Brees |website=New Orleans Saints |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322142729/http://www.neworleanssaints.com/media-center/videos/Top-100-Drew-Brees/82bbf7d9-60e3-4048-8aab-2a3610c676f1 |archive-date=March 22, 2018 |access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2011 season====\n{{see also|2011 New Orleans Saints season#Individual Records Set or Tied}}\nThe [[2011 NFL season|2011 season]] was a record-breaking season for Brees as he led the NFL in completion percentage, passing yards and passing touchdowns, which is known as the \"Triple Crown\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-network-total-access/0ap2000000356600/NFL-Triple-Crown-winners |title=NFL Triple Crown winners |date=June 7, 2014 |publisher=[[National Football League|NFL]]}}</ref> He broke [[Dan Marino]]'s 27-year-old record for most passing yards in one season (5,084) in the 15th game of the season (week 16) against the [[2011 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] at home in [[New Orleans]] at the [[Mercedes-Benz Superdome]] with a touchdown pass to [[Darren Sproles]]. Brees also set a new Saints franchise record for passing touchdowns in a season with 46.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nfl/recap?gameId=311226018 |title=Drew Brees sets single-season passing record as Saints clinch NFC South |date=December 26, 2011 |publisher=[[ESPN]] |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 2, during the Saints' home-opener, Brees defeated the [[2011 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] for the first time in his career as a starting quarterback, leaving the [[Baltimore Ravens]] as the only remaining NFL team which Brees had never beaten to that point.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201109180nor.htm |title=Chicago Bears at New Orleans Saints \u2013 September 18th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> On October 23, in a 62\u20137 victory over the [[2011 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]], he was 31 of 35 for 325 passing yards and five touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201110230nor.htm |title=Indianapolis Colts at New Orleans Saints \u2013 October 23rd, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref> He earned NFC Offensive Player of the Week for his performance against the Colts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2011/week_7.htm |title=2011 NFL Week 7 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> On November 28, a Week 12 49\u201324 victory over the [[2011 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], he had 363 passing yards and four touchdowns to earn NFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201111280nor.htm |title=New York Giants at New Orleans Saints \u2013 November 28th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2011/week_12.htm |title=2011 NFL Week 12 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> In a home game on December 4 against the [[2011 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]], Brees passed for 342 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201112040nor.htm |title=Detroit Lions at New Orleans Saints \u2013 December 4th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> Brees' performance gave him 4,031 yards on the season, making him the first quarterback in NFL history to eclipse the 4,000-yard mark in the first 12 games of a season, and the first quarterback to reach four consecutive seasons with 4,000+ yards and 30+ [[touchdown pass]]es. In week 15 against the [[2011 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]], Brees threw for 412 yards with five passing touchdowns. With that game, Brees became the first quarterback in NFL history to throw for five touchdowns, 400+ yards, while also maintaining a completion percentage of 80%, in a game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201112180min.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Minnesota Vikings \u2013 December 18th, 2011 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/pgl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=game&year_min=1950&year_max=2016&season_start=1&season_end=-1&age_min=0&age_max=0&pos=0&game_type=R&career_game_num_min=0&career_game_num_max=499&game_num_min=0&game_num_max=99&week_num_min=0&week_num_max=99&c1stat=pass_yds&c1comp=gt&c1val=400&c2stat=pass_td&c2comp=gt&c2val=5&c3stat=pass_cmp_perc&c3comp=gt&c3val=80&c4stat=choose&c4comp=gt&c5comp=choose&c5gtlt=lt&c6mult=1.0&c6comp=choose&order_by=game_date |title=400+ pass yds, 5+ TD, 80% comp |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |access-date=December 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 16 against the [[2011 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] at the [[Mercedes-Benz Superdome]], Brees broke Dan Marino's long standing record of passing yards in a single season of 5,084 with a nine-yard touchdown pass to [[Darren Sproles]] with just under three minutes left in the fourth quarter of the game. He needed 305 yards to break the record entering the game and exceeded that mark with 307. He ended the game having thrown for 5,087 total passing yards for the regular season with one regular season game remaining. With his second-quarter, eight-yard touchdown pass to [[Marques Colston]], Brees extended his streak of consecutive games with a touchdown pass to 42 games. Marino congratulated Brees via [[Twitter]] after the game, saying \"Congrats to @drewbrees. Great job by such a special player.\" Brees responded by tweeting, \"Thanks to [https://www.twitter.com/DanMarino @DanMarino] for his class and support during this run. It is an honor to attempt to follow the example he set for us all.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://twitter.com/drewbrees/status/151564613664772096 |title=Thanks to @DanMarino for his class and support during this run. It is an honor to attempt to follow the example he set for us all |last=Brees |first=Drew |date=December 26, 2011 |website=Twitter}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2011/12/first-and-10_23.html |title=Records keep piling up for the New Orleans Saints: First-and-10 |last=Duncan |first=Jeff |date=December 30, 2011 |work=[[The Times-Picayune]] |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> He earned his third and final NFC Offensive Player of the Week honor for the 2011 season with his performance against the Falcons.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2011/week_16.htm |title=2011 NFL Week 16 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 17 against the [[2011 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]], Brees closed out the season by setting six NFL records, finishing the year with 468 completions for 5,476 yards, edging [[Tom Brady]] of the [[New England Patriots]], who also surpassed Marino's record with 5,235 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2012/01/01/drew-brees-tom-brady-matthew-stafford-all-top-5000-yards/ |title=Drew Brees, Tom Brady, Matthew Stafford all top 5,000 yards |last=Smith |first=Michael David |date=January 1, 2012 |website=ProFootballTalk |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> Brees averaged 342.25 yards passing per game, which broke [[Dan Fouts]]' record of 320.3 in a strike-shortened {{nfly|1982}} season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/pass_yds_per_g_single_season.htm |title=NFL Single-Season Passing Yards per Game Leaders |website=pro-football-reference.com |access-date=January 3, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203430404577094751107933064 |title=The NFL's Mount Passmore |last=Cacciola |first=Scott |date=December 13, 2011 |work=The Wall Street Journal |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/64QgVJ2qu?url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052970203430404577094751107933064.html |archive-date=January 4, 2012}}</ref> In 2013, [[Peyton Manning]] bested Brees' record by one passing yard, and finished the season with an NFL-record 5,477 passing yards, averaging 342.31 yards per game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap2000000305757/article/peyton-manning-sets-mark-for-passing-yards-in-season |title=Peyton Manning sets mark for passing yards in season |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> In the NFC [[2011\u201312 NFL playoffs#NFC: New Orleans Saints 45, Detroit Lions 28|Wild Card Round]], Brees passed for 466 yards and three passing touchdowns as the Saints defeated the [[2011 Detroit Lions|Detroit Lions]] by a score of 45\u201328.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201070nor.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Detroit Lions at New Orleans Saints \u2013 January 7th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> However, Brees and the Saints lost in the [[2011\u201312 NFL playoffs#NFC: San Francisco 49ers 36, New Orleans Saints 32|Divisional Round]] to the [[2011 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]] by a score of 36\u201332 in a back-and-forth contest.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/15/sports/football/49ers-beat-saints-in-a-shootout.html |title=49ers Beat Saints in a Shootout |last=Branch |first=John |date=January 14, 2012 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=August 22, 2019}}</ref> In the loss, Brees passed for 462 passing yards, four passing touchdowns, and two interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201201140sfo.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 New Orleans Saints at San Francisco 49ers \u2013 January 14th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> He was named to his sixth career Pro Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2011/probowl.htm |title=2011 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked as the second-best player in the league by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2012]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/new-orleans-saints/09000d5d82a2ae47/The-Top-100-Players-of-2012-Drew-Brees |title='The Top 100: Players of 2012': Drew Brees |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2012 season====\n[[File:Brees 2013 Pro Bowl Cropped.jpg|thumb|Brees at the [[2013 Pro Bowl]]]]\n{{See also|2012 New Orleans Saints season}}\nOn July 13, the Saints and Brees agreed to a five-year, $100 million contract. The contract included the largest amount of guaranteed money in NFL history, at $60 million. $40 million of the contract was paid the first year.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/8163701/sources-drew-brees-new-orleans-saints-agree-record-contract |title=Sources: Drew Brees, Saints agree |last=Mortensen |first=Chris |date=July 13, 2012 |work=espn.com |access-date=July 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBrees started the season with 339 passing yards, three touchdowns, and two interceptions in a 40\u201332 loss to the [[2012 Washington Redskins|Washington Redskins]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209090nor.htm |title=Washington Redskins at New Orleans Saints - September 9th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> In Week 4, he passed for 446 yards and three touchdowns in a 28\u201327 loss to the [[2012 Green Bay Packers|Green Bay Packers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201209300gnb.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Green Bay Packers - September 30th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> In Week 5, Brees threw a 40-yard touchdown pass to [[Devery Henderson]] against his former team, the [[2012 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]]. This was his 48th consecutive game with a touchdown pass. With that touchdown pass, Brees broke [[Johnny Unitas]]'s consecutive game streak with at least one touchdown pass, and Unitas' son Joe was present at the Superdome to witness his father's 52-year-old record being broken.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-films-presents/0ap2000000099541/NFL-Films-Presents-Brees-breaks-Unitas-record |title='NFL Films Presents': Brees breaks Unitas' record |date=November 24, 2012 |publisher=[[National Football League|NFL]]}}</ref> [[Sean Payton]], [[Joe Vitt]] and [[Mickey Loomis]], who were all serving suspensions due to the \"[[New Orleans Saints bounty scandal|Bountygate]]\" scandal, were granted permission to watch the Week 5 game against the [[San Diego Chargers]] due to Brees potentially breaking Unitas' record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://wap.nfl.com/news/0ap1000000069267/brees-request-allows-payton-vitt-to-attend-saints-game |title=SEAN PAYTON, JOE VITT ALLOWED TO ATTEND SAINTS GAME |last=Copeland |first=Kareem |date=October 3, 2012 |publisher=NFL |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121006234042/http://wap.nfl.com/news/0ap1000000069267/brees-request-allows-payton-vitt-to-attend-saints-game/ |archive-date=October 6, 2012 |access-date=October 3, 2012}}</ref> Brees earned NFC Offensive Player of the Week for his 370-yard, four-touchdown, and one-interception effort against the Chargers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201210070nor.htm |title=San Diego Chargers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 October 7th, 2012 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2012/week_5.htm |title=2012 NFL Week 5 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> Without their head coach, the Saints had lost their first four games but ended the losing streak with a 31\u201324 win over the Chargers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nor/2012.htm |title=2012 New Orleans Saints Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the Week 13 game against the [[2012 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Brees threw no touchdowns and a career-high five interceptions, ending his consecutive game streak with at least one touchdown pass at 54.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/nfl/gameflash/2012/11/29/5069/?hpt=hp_t3 |title=Falcons pick off Brees 5 times, beat Saints 23\u201313 |work=CNN |access-date=November 30, 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929002945/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/football/nfl/gameflash/2012/11/29/5069/?hpt=hp_t3 |archive-date=September 29, 2013}}</ref> In Week 14, against the [[2012 New York Giants|New York Giants]], Brees threw for 354 yards, giving him his seventh straight 4,000-yard passing season, surpassing [[Peyton Manning]]'s record of sixth straight seasons.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.neworleansprofootball.com/2012/12/underpowered-in-ny-giants-wilson-pound.html |title=Underpowered In NY: Giants, Wilson Pound Mistake-Prone Saints 52-27 |date=December 9, 2012 |website=New Orleans Pro Football |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> It was also his fifth straight season with at least 30 touchdown passes and 4,000 yards passing, also an NFL record. Brees managed to finish the 2012 season with 5,177 passing yards and 43 touchdowns despite having the worst defensive support in the NFL, whose 7,042 yards conceded was an all-time NFL record, and the team finished the season with a 7\u20139 record and missed the playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1568281-new-orleans-saints-the-2012-defense-broke-a-record-and-the-bank |title=New Orleans Saints: The 2012 Defense Broke a Record and the Bank |last=Raborn |first=Tyler |website=Bleacher Report |language=en |access-date=August 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nor/2012.htm |title=2012 New Orleans Saints Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor the seventh time, Brees was selected to the [[2013 Pro Bowl]], this time as an injury replacement for [[Robert Griffin III]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap1000000124329/article/drew-brees-replacing-injured-rg3-on-nfcs-pro-bowl-roster |title=Drew Brees replacing injured RG3 on NFC's Pro Bowl roster |date=January 9, 2013 |website=[[National Football League]] |access-date=January 9, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2012/probowl.htm |title=2012 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked 11th by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2013]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/new-orleans-saints/0ap2000000212740/Thomas-Morstead-Russell-Wilson-Jermond-Bushrod-Gerald-McCoy |title='Top 100 Players of 2013': Drew Brees |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2013 season====\n{{See also|2013 New Orleans Saints season}}\nBrees started the 2013 season with 357 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception in the 23\u201317 home victory over the [[2013 Atlanta Falcons|Atlanta Falcons]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309080nor.htm |title=Atlanta Falcons at New Orleans Saints - September 8th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> In Week 4, a 38\u201317 home victory over the [[2013 Miami Dolphins season|Miami Dolphins]], he had 413 passing yards and four touchdowns to earn NFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201309300nor.htm |title=Miami Dolphins at New Orleans Saints \u2013 September 30th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2013/week_4.htm |title=2013 NFL Week 4 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> In Week 10, a 49\u201317 victory over the [[2013 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]], he had 392 passing yards and four touchdowns to earn another NFC Offensive Player of the Week honor.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201311100nor.htm |title=Dallas Cowboys at New Orleans Saints \u2013 November 10th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2013/week_10.htm |title=2013 NFL Week 10 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> In Week 12, Brees passed [[Warren Moon]] for fifth on the career passing yards list with 49,566. During Week 14, Brees became the fastest player ever to join the 50,000-yard club and only the fifth player to do so.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2013/12/drew-brees-50000-passing-yards |title=Drew Brees joins the 50,000-yard club |last=McGarry |first=Tim |date=December 8, 2013 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> He did it in 183 games, passing the 50,000 milestone on a pass to [[Jimmy Graham]] in the fourth quarter of a 31\u201313 Saints win over the [[2013 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]] on December 8, in which he threw four touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201312080nor.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 December 8th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> In Week 17, a 42\u201317 victory over the [[2013 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], he had 381 passing yards and four touchdowns to earn his third NFC Offensive Player of the Week nod for the 2013 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201312290nor.htm |title=Tampa Bay Buccaneers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 December 29th, 2013 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2013/week_17.htm |title=2013 NFL Week 17 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> Brees also extended his NFL record to a sixth straight season of at least 30 touchdown passes with 4,000 passing yards, his third straight 5,000-yard season, and his eighth straight 4,000-yard season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2013/12/08/sunday-night-wrap-up-brees-joins-select-company |title=Sunday night wrap-up: Brees joins select company |last=Gantt |first=Darin |date=December 8, 2013 |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> For his successful performance in 2013, he was named to his eighth career Pro Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2013/probowl.htm |title=2013 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> The Saints finished with an 11\u20135 record and narrowly defeated the [[2013 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] in the [[2013\u201314 NFL playoffs#NFC: New Orleans Saints 26, Philadelphia Eagles 24|Wild Card Round]], but lost to the [[2013 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] in the [[2013\u201314 NFL playoffs#NFC: Seattle Seahawks 23, New Orleans Saints 15|Divisional Round]], who went on to win [[Super Bowl XLVIII]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/schedules/2013/POST |title=NFL 2013 Playoff Schedule - NFL.com |access-date=November 27, 2016}}</ref> He finished ranked sixth by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2014]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/new-orleans-saints/0ap2000000363944 |title='Top 100 Players of 2014': Drew Brees |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2014 season====\n{{See also|2014 New Orleans Saints season}}\nBrees admits that the 2014 season was his \"most frustrating\".<ref name=\"King\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/2015/01/26/drew-brees-new-orleans-saints |title=An Aging Star, A Lost Season |last=King |first=Peter |date=January 4, 2016 |website=SI.com |publisher=Time Inc. |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> The Saints finished with a 7\u20139 record and missed the playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2014/12/30/payton-promises-change-after-saints-go-7-9/21064105/ |title=Payton promises change after Saints go 7-9 |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> Brees' 2014 season began with a pair of games lost on game-ending field goals by the other team; in Week 1, the Saints lost 37\u201334 on the road to the [[2014 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]] in overtime and in Week 2, in a 26\u201324 road loss to the [[2014 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], he moved into fourth place on the [[List of National Football League passing yardage leaders|career passing yardage]] list, ahead of [[John Elway]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409070atl.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Atlanta Falcons \u2013 September 7th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201409140cle.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Cleveland Browns \u2013 September 14th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/new-orleans-saints/post/_/id/9589/colston-shut-out-brees-passes-elway |title=Colston shut out; Brees passes Elway |last=Triplett |first=Mike |date=September 15, 2014 |work=[[ESPN.com]] |access-date=September 15, 2014}}</ref> On October 19, in a road game against the [[2014 Detroit Lions|Detroit Lions]], Brees became the NFL's all-time leader in completion percentage at 66.21%, surpassing [[Chad Pennington]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/pass_cmp_perc_career.htm |title=NFL Career Pass Completion % Leaders |publisher=Pro Football Reference |access-date=December 30, 2010}}</ref> On November 30, in a Week 13 35\u201332 road victory over the [[2014 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]], he had 257 passing yards and five touchdowns to earn NFC Offensive Player of the Week, which was the 20th time in his career he has earned the award over his career in both the AFC with the Chargers and the NFC with the Saints.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201411300pit.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Pittsburgh Steelers \u2013 November 30th, 2014 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/week_13.htm |title=2014 NFL Week 13 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> In a Week 15 road game against the [[2014 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]], he extended his streak to an NFL-record seventh straight season with at least 30 touchdown passes and nine straight seasons of 4,000 passing yards. However his streak of 5,000 passing yard seasons ended at three, as he passed for 4,952 yards, which was good enough to tie him with Steelers quarterback [[Ben Roethlisberger]] for the most passing yards in the league that season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2014/12/drew_brees_extends_records_in.html |title=Drew Brees extends records in near-perfect game vs. Chicago |last=Terrell |first=Katherine |date=December 15, 2014 |work=[[The Times-Picayune]] |access-date=December 16, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2014/12/30/brees-roethlisberger-have-nfls-first-tie-for-passing-yardage-lead/ |title=Brees, Roethlisberger have NFL\u2019s first tie for passing yardage lead |last=Smith |first=Michael David |date=December 30, 2014 |website=ProFootballTalk |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He was named to his seventh consecutive and ninth career Pro Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/probowl.htm |title=2014 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked 30th by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2015]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2015/0ap3000000498550/Top-100-Players-of-2015-No-30-Drew-Brees |title='Top 100 Players of 2015': No. 30 Drew Brees |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=March 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Drew Brees 2015.jpg|thumb|Brees in 2015 in [[Fedex Field|Landover]]]]\n\n====2015 season====\n{{See also|2015 New Orleans Saints season}}\nBrees and the Saints started the 2015 season with an 0\u20133 start with two of the losses being by one possession. On October 4, 2015, in Week 4, his 80-yard touchdown pass to [[C. J. Spiller]] on the second play of overtime gave the Saints a 26\u201320 victory over the [[2015 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas Cowboys]], and the team's first win of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wlox.com/story/30184225/drew-brees-and-cj-spiller-help-saints-win-a-thriller-in-ot-against-dallas |title=Drew Brees and C.J. Spiller help Saints win a thriller in OT against Dallas |last=Giardina |first=A. J. |website=WLOX |language=en-US |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He earned NFC Offensive Player of the Week for his effort against the Cowboys.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201510040nor.htm |title=Dallas Cowboys at New Orleans Saints \u2013 October 4th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2015/week_4.htm |title=2015 NFL Week 4 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref> The touchdown gave Brees 400 for his career, making him the fifth player in NFL history to reach the 400 touchdown milestone. Also, he became the fastest player ever to reach 400 touchdowns, doing so in 205 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nola.com/sports/saints/article_769cd00f-241f-53bb-9c8c-5612ac21afbe.html |title='This rarely happens': Saints quarterback Drew Brees joins elite 400 club in unforgettable fashion |last=Erickson |first=Joel |website=NOLA.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> Brees also completed his 5,000th pass with a touchdown to tight end [[Josh Hill (American football)|Josh Hill]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2015/10/saints_cowboys_recap.html |title=Saints-Cowboys recap |last=Woodbery |first=Evan |date=October 4, 2015 |work=NOLA.com |access-date=April 19, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/drew-brees-throws-for-400th-touchdown--5-000th-career-completion-011955640.html |title=Drew Brees wins game with 400th career touchdown |last=Busbee |first=Jay |website=Yahoo! Sports |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909010950/https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nfl-shutdown-corner/drew-brees-throws-for-400th-touchdown--5-000th-career-completion-011955640.html |archive-date=September 9, 2017 |access-date=November 15, 2015}}</ref> It was the quickest regular season overtime win in the history of the NFL at 13 seconds.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2015/10/new-orleans-saints-win-dallas-cowboys-drew-brees-cj-spiller-tony-romo-fastest-overtime-win-nfl-history |title=Saints set record with overtime win over Cowboys |last=Chase |first=Chris |date=October 4, 2015 |publisher=ftw.usatoday.com |access-date=February 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, 2015, Brees tied the NFL record of touchdown passes in a game with seven during a 52\u201349 Saints win over the [[2015 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/story/_/id/14027913/drew-brees-new-orleans-saints-ties-nfl-mark-7-tds-eli-manning-newyork-giants-top-10-all-tds |title=Drew Brees ties NFL mark with 7 TDs; Eli Manning top 10 all-time in TDs |last=Triplett |first=Mike |date=November 1, 2015 |work=[[ESPN]] |access-date=November 1, 2015 |last2=Graziano |first2=Dan}}</ref> In that game, he completed 39-of-50 passes for 505 yards to record his second career game with at least 500 passing yards.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dubin |first1=Jared |title=Drew Brees ties NFL record with seven TD passes against Giants |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25360491/drew-brees-ties-nfl-record-with-7th-td-pass-of-the-game |website=CBS Sports |accessdate=November 2, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151102195147/http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25360491/drew-brees-ties-nfl-record-with-7th-td-pass-of-the-game |archivedate=November 2, 2015 |date=November 1, 2015}}</ref> He became the second player in NFL history to have multiple 500-yard passing games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newsday.com/sports/football/nfl-500-yard-passers-in-a-game-1.26542194 |title=500-yard NFL passers in a game |website=Newsday |language=en |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref> He earned NFC Offensive Player of the Week for his historic performance against the New York Giants.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2015/week_8.htm |title=2015 NFL Week 8 Leaders & Scores |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 12, his streak of 45 consecutive games with a touchdown pass ended in a 24\u20136 loss at [[2015 Houston Texans season|Houston]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201511290htx.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Houston Texans \u2013 November 29th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> Two weeks later, he surpassed [[Dan Marino]] for fourth in career touchdown passes as the Saints beat the [[2015 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] by a score of 24\u201317.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-game-highlights/0ap3000000599785/Drew-Brees-passes-Dan-Marino-for-fourth-all-time-in-TD-passes |title=Drew Brees passes Dan Marino for fourth all-time in TD passes |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> In Week 15, he became the fourth quarterback to reach the 60,000-yard milestone\u2014in 215 games, the fastest ever\u2014and had his 10th straight 4,000-yard season, plus his 94th 300-yard game, but the [[2015 Detroit Lions season|Detroit Lions]] won 35\u201327. This put him first in most 300-yard games as Brees and [[Peyton Manning|Manning]] had been tied at 93 games prior to that game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2015/12/new_orleans_saints_drew_brees_76.html |title=Drew Brees sets NFL record with 94th career 300-yard passing game. |last=Dabe |first=Christopher |date=December 22, 2015 |website=NOLA.com |access-date=November 27, 2016}}</ref> A week later, his streak was extended to an eighth straight season with at least 30 touchdown passes, plus his 95th 300-yarder, all NFL records, against the [[2015 Jacksonville Jaguars season|Jacksonville Jaguars]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=400791528 |title=Brees sharp despite foot injury, Saints beat Jaguars 38\u201327 |date=December 27, 2015 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=November 27, 2016 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> With a Week 17 win over the [[2015 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Brees finished the season with four straight 300-yard games, for a career record total of 96, and a season total 4,870 yards passing, leading the league in passing yards for a record sixth time despite missing one game due to an injury.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nola.com/sports/saints/article_8f7f8c30-58b3-5c4d-93a3-c358202b27a5.html |title=Drew Brees ends season as NFL passing leader for a record sixth time |last=Dabe |first=Christopher |website=NOLA.com |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> Despite the accomplishments on the field, the Saints finished with a 7\u20139 record and missed the playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2016/01/05/saints-await-paytons-plans-after-second-straight-7-9-record/78310834/ |title=Saints await Payton's plans after second straight 7-9 record |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He was ranked 30th by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2016]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2016/0ap3000000670938/Top-100-Players-of-2016-No-30-Drew-Brees |title='Top 100 Players of 2016': No. 30 Drew Brees |website=NFL.com |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\n{{See also|2016 New Orleans Saints season}}\n{{external media|video1={{YouTube|fVdbPHcy38Q|Video of Brees throwing an 87-yard touchdown pass to Brandin Cooks}}}}\nIn the Saints' 2016 season opener, Brees threw a career-high 98-yard touchdown pass to [[Brandin Cooks]] in a narrow 35\u201334 home loss to the [[2016 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]].<ref name=RadiersSaints/> He finished the game 28\u2013of\u201342 for 423 yards and four touchdown passes.<ref name=RadiersSaints/> His 400-yard performance tied him with Peyton Manning for the most 400-yard passing games in NFL history.<ref name=\"RadiersSaints\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/nfl/story/raiders-withstand-drew-brees-monster-game-to-win-thriller-091116 |title=Raiders withstand Drew Brees' monster game to win thriller |date=September 11, 2016 |website=foxsports.com |access-date=January 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=NOLA/> The next week, he passed [[Dan Marino]] for third place in career passing yards in a loss to the [[2016 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/17576827/drew-brees-new-orleans-saints-passes-dan-marino-career-yardage-list |title=Drew Brees moves to third in career passing yards in loss to Giants |last=Triplett |first=Mike |date=September 18, 2016 |website=ESPN |access-date=January 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn October 16, in Week 6, Brees threw for 465 yards and four touchdown passes with one interception in a 41\u201338 home win over the [[2016 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201610160nor.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 October 16th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> With this performance, Brees set an NFL record with the 15th 400-yard passing performance of his career.<ref name=\"fourhrecord\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/17809654/drew-brees-new-orleans-saints-sets-nfl-mark-400-yard-games-win |title=Drew Brees sets NFL record with 15th 400-yard passing game |authors=ESPN.com news services |date=October 16, 2016 |website=espn.com |access-date=February 15, 2018}}</ref> Brees reached another milestone in the game, becoming the sixth player to record 50,000 passing yards with one team. The other five players are Peyton Manning (Indianapolis Colts), [[Brett Favre]] (Green Bay Packers), Dan Marino (Miami Dolphins), [[Tom Brady]] (New England Patriots), and [[John Elway]] (Denver Broncos).<ref name=\"NOLA\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2016/10/saints_panthers_numbers_2016.html |title=Drew Brees tops Peyton Manning for most 400-yard games, and other key numbers from Sunday |last=Dabe |first=Christopher |date=October 16, 2016 |website=NOLA.com |access-date=October 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 7, Brees became the first player in NFL history with 100 games of 300+ passing yards, in a loss against the [[2016 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]] on October 23.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.todayspigskin.com/nfl-news/saints-drew-brees-becomes-first-with-100-300-yard-passing-games/ |title=Saints' Drew Brees Becomes First With 100 300-Yard Passing Games |website=www.todayspigskin.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909052909/https://www.todayspigskin.com/nfl-news/saints-drew-brees-becomes-first-with-100-300-yard-passing-games/ |archive-date=September 9, 2017 |access-date=March 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.neworleanssaints.com/video/drew-brees-becomes-first-player-with-100-games-of-300-pass-yards-17942062 |title=Drew Brees becomes first player with 100 games of 300 passing yards |website=NewOrleansSaints.com |access-date=November 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring Week 16, Brees and [[Aaron Rodgers]] tied the NFL record for most seasons with at least 35 touchdown passes with four\u2014a record shared with [[Peyton Manning]] and [[Tom Brady]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/ww1Iz |title=Most seasons 35+ pass TD career |website=pro-football-reference.com |access-date=December 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"mosttdpass\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/pass_td_single_season.htm |title=NFL Single-Season Passing Touchdowns Leaders |website=pro-football-reference.com |access-date=December 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nBrees finished the 2016 season leading the league in passing yards with 5,208, the second most of his career and the fifth 5,000-yard season of his career\u2014more than all other 5,000-yard seasons combined (4).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2684786-drew-brees-has-more-5000-yard-seasons-than-all-other-qbs-in-history-combined |title=Drew Brees Has More 5,000-Yard Seasons Than All Other QBs in History Combined |authors=Bleacher Report Insights |date=January 2, 2017 |website=Bleacher Report |access-date=January 4, 2017}}</ref> He threw for 471 completions, breaking his NFL record of 468 set in 2011, and a career-high 673 attempts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://saintswire.usatoday.com/2017/07/04/new-orleans-saints-drew-brees-completion-record-brett-favre-peyton-manning-opponents-game-by-game/ |title=Game by Game: Getting Saints' Brees to NFL's career completion record |date=July 4, 2017 |website=Saints Wire |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> Brees finished third in touchdown passes with 37, the fourth most of his career. He finished second in completion percentage (70.0%),<ref name=\"2016leaderspfr\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/leaders.htm |title=2016 NFL Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference |publisher=Sports Reference LLC |access-date=January 4, 2017}}</ref> making it the third time he has completed at least 70% of his passes in a season.{{efn|The norm for NFL completion percentage is to round to the nearest tenth, but technically speaking, Brees only completed 69.985% of his passes.}} Despite his performance, for the third straight season, the Saints finished 7\u20139 and missed the playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/blog/new-orleans-saints/post/_/id/25130 |title=Saints stuck in 7-9 rut but have faith 2017 will be better |last=Triplett |first=Mike |date=January 1, 2017 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He was named to his tenth career Pro Bowl for his 2016 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2016/probowl.htm |title=2016 NFL Pro Bowlers |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> He was ranked 16th by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000816416/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-16-Drew-Brees |title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 16 Drew Brees |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\n{{See also|2017 New Orleans Saints season}}\nAfter starting off the 2017 season with a 29\u201319 loss to the [[2017 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]] on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'', Brees looked to bounce back in Week 2 against the [[2017 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]]. In the 36\u201320 loss, he was 27-of-45 for 356 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/north/story/minnesota-vikings-sam-bradford-stefon-diggs-adam-thielen-new-orleans-saints-drew-brees-091117 |title=Vikings offense erupts in 29-19 win over New Orleans |website=FOX Sports |language=en-US |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709170nor.htm |title=New England Patriots at New Orleans Saints \u2013 September 17th, 2017 |website=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |access-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\nDuring Week 10 against the [[2017 Buffalo Bills season|Buffalo Bills]], Brees was held to 184 passing yards, but the Saints combined for 298 rushing yards and won 47\u201310.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201711120buf.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Buffalo Bills \u2013 November 12th, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=December 30, 2017}}</ref> In Week 13, he passed [[Peyton Manning]] for second place in career completions in a 31\u201321 victory over the Carolina Panthers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theadvocate.com/new_orleans/sports/saints/article_320c9c04-d896-11e7-9a59-7fa18b347aa5.html |title=Drew Brees passes Peyton Manning, moves into second place on career completions list |last=Erickson |first=Joel |date=December 3, 2017 |website=The Advocate |language=en |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> On December 19, 2017, Brees was named to his 11th career Pro Bowl.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000895772/article/nfl-announces-2018-pro-bowl-rosters |title=NFL announces 2018 Pro Bowl rosters |authors=Around the NFL staff |date=December 19, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=December 26, 2017}}</ref> During Week 16 against the [[2017 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Brees became the third player to amass over 70,000 passing yards in a career, doing so in an NFL fastest 248 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.12up.com/posts/5928455-drew-brees-makes-nfl-history-with-incredible-career-milestone |title=Drew Brees Makes NFL History With Incredible Career Milestone |last=Brown |first=Nick |date=December 24, 2017 |website=12up.com |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> In that game he also earned his 12th straight 4,000-yard season and finished the game with 239 passing yards, a touchdown, and an interception as the Saints won 23\u201313.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000897268/article/drew-brees-becomes-fastest-qb-to-70000-yards |title=Drew Brees reaches milestone of 70,000 passing yards |authors=Around the NFL staff |date=December 24, 2017 |publisher=NFL |access-date=December 24, 2017}}</ref> Brees finished the 2017 season by setting a then-NFL record 72.0 completion percentage.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2017/12/drew_brees_posts_highest_compl.html |title=Drew Brees posts highest completion percentage in NFL history |last=Morale III |first=Amos |date=December 31, 2017 |website=NOLA.com |access-date=January 2, 2018}}</ref> He also led the league in number of completions (386) and yards per pass attempt (8.1), and came in second in passer rating (103.9).<ref name=\"pfrstats\">{{cite web |title=Drew Brees Stats |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BreeDr00.htm |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |accessdate=September 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Saints finished with an 11\u20135 record, won the NFC South, and returned to the playoffs for the first time since the 2013 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/nor/2017.htm |title=2017 New Orleans Saints Statistics & Players |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#NFC: New Orleans Saints 31, Carolina Panthers 26|Wild Card Round]] against the [[2017 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]], he had 376 passing yards, two touchdowns, and one interception in the 31\u201326 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801070nor.htm |title=Wild Card \u2013 Carolina Panthers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 January 7th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318 NFL playoffs#NFC: Minnesota Vikings 29, New Orleans Saints 24|Divisional Round]] against the [[2017 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]], he had 294 passing yards, three touchdowns, and two interceptions in the [[Minneapolis Miracle|29\u201324 loss]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201801140min.htm |title=Divisional Round \u2013 New Orleans Saints at Minnesota Vikings \u2013 January 14th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/sports/college/purdue/2018/01/14/vikings-beat-saints-drew-brees-most-bonkers-game-ending-play/1033095001/ |title=Vikings beat Saints, Drew Brees on the most bonkers game-ending play |website=Indianapolis Star |language=en |access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref> He was ranked eighth by his fellow players on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2018]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2018/0ap3000000938437/Top-100-Players-of-2018-Drew-Brees-No-8 |title='Top 100 Players of 2018': New Orleans Saints quarterback Drew Brees {{!}} No. 8 |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=October 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\n{{See also|2018 New Orleans Saints season}}\nOn March 13, 2018, Brees signed a two-year, $50 million contract extension with the Saints with $27 million guaranteed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000920839/article/drew-brees-saints-agree-to-twoyear-50-million-deal |title=Drew Brees, Saints agree on two-year, $50 million deal |last=Sessler |first=Marc |date=March 13, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Week 1, Brees threw for more than 400 yards for a record 16th time in his career, but the [[2018 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] won 48\u201340.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2018/09/saints_bucs_column_2.html |title=Nobody saw this coming: Saints dealt worst opening loss of Payton-Brees era |last=Duncan |first=Jeff |date=September 9, 2018 |work=NOLA.com |access-date=March 15, 2019}}</ref> In Week 3 against the [[2018 Atlanta Falcons season|Atlanta Falcons]], Brees broke Brett Favre's record for career pass completions in the second quarter with his 6,301st career completion.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2018/09/23/sports/football/23reuters-football-nfl-no-brees-record.html |title=Brees Breaks Favre's Record for Completions |date=September 23, 2018 |website=The New York Times |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180924000834/https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2018/09/23/sports/football/23reuters-football-nfl-no-brees-record.html |archive-date=September 24, 2018 |access-date=September 23, 2018 |agency=Reuters}}</ref> In that game, a 43\u201337 overtime Saints victory, Brees threw for 396 yards and three touchdowns, and also ran for two more scores, including the game-winner in overtime, earning him NFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000966754/article/big-ben-drew-brees-among-nfl-players-of-the-week |title=Big Ben, Drew Brees among NFL Players of the Week. On October 8th, Bree's broke the record for most passing yards in NFL history. |last=Bergman |first=Jeremy |date=September 26, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 15, 2019}}</ref> In Week 5 on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' against the [[2018 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]], Brees broke Peyton Manning's all-time passing yardage record with a 62-yard touchdown pass to [[Tre'Quan Smith]] late in the second quarter.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/saints/2018/10/08/saints-drew-brees-overtakes-peyton-manning-all-time-passing-yards/1559346002/ |title=Drew Brees overtakes Peyton Manning to become NFL's career passing leader as Saints crush Redskins |last=Davis |first=Nate |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He went on to complete 26 of 29 passes, setting a then career-high 89.66 single-game completion percentage, for 363 yards and three touchdowns in the 43\u201319 victory, earning him NFC Offensive Player of the Week for the second time in three weeks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000972353/article/drew-brees-isaiah-crowell-among-players-of-the-week |title=Drew Brees, Isaiah Crowell among Players of the Week |last=Maya |first=Adam |date=October 10, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 15, 2019}}</ref> Following a bye week, Brees finally claimed his first career victory against the [[2018 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]] with a score of 24\u201323, making him the third quarterback in NFL history to beat all 32 teams, joining Peyton Manning and Brett Favre.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.canalstreetchronicles.com/2018/10/21/18006922/drew-brees-becomes-third-quarterback-beat-all-32-nfl-teams-ravens-peyton-manning-brett-favre |title=Drew Brees becomes 3rd quarterback to beat all 32 NFL teams |last=Hendrix |first=John |date=October 21, 2019 |work=Canal Street Chronicles |access-date=October 29, 2018}}</ref> During this game, Brees also became the fourth quarterback in NFL history, along with Manning, Favre, and [[Tom Brady]], to reach 500 career touchdown passes when he threw a 1-yard touchdown to [[Benjamin Watson]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/saints/2018/10/21/drew-brees-new-orleans-saints-500-touchdown-passes/1723248002/ |title=Saints QB Drew Brees throws 500th career TD pass |last=Bell |first=Jarrett |date=October 21, 2018 |website=USA Today |access-date=October 21, 2018}}</ref> After a season-low 120 yards and his first interception of the season in a win over the [[2018 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201810280min.htm |title=New Orleans Saints at Minnesota Vikings \u2013 October 28th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en}}</ref> Brees logged 346 yards, four touchdowns, and zero interceptions to hand the [[2018 Los Angeles Rams season|Rams]] their first loss of the season in Week 9.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/patriots/2018/11/04/drew-brees-saints-hand-rams-first-loss-season/J0Vbf2DWnSfAVze9Dh02EM/story.html |title=Drew Brees, Saints hand Rams first loss of the season |last=Martel |first=Brett |date=November 4, 2018 |website=BostonGlobe.com |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> In a Week 10 matchup against the [[2018 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]], Brees passed Brett Favre for second in career passing touchdowns with a 17-yard touchdown to [[Michael Thomas (wide receiver, born 1993)|Michael Thomas]] in a 51\u201314 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://apnews.com/8f12634a1cd34af89fe15f4a6a0972f8 |title=Brees passes Favre with 3 TDs, Saints crush Bengals 51\u201314 |last=Kay |first=Joe |date=November 12, 2018 |website=AP NEWS |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref> Brees was named the NFC Offensive Player of the Month for his performance during the month of November.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.neworleanssaints.com/news/drew-brees-named-nfc-offensive-player-of-the-month-for-november?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook |title=Drew Brees named NFC Offensive Player of the Month for November |date=November 29, 2018 |website=New Orleans Saints |language=en-US |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBrees finished the season with 364 completions, 489 attempts, 3,992 passing yards, 32 passing touchdowns and five interceptions over 15 games.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/2019/07/27/saints-qb-brees-im-still-green/39815189/ |title=Saints QB Brees: I'm still green |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He sat out the season finale after the Saints had clinched the NFC's #1 seed the week prior.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/saints/2018/12/23/new-orleans-saints-clinch-top-seed-dent-steelers-playoff-hopes/2404312002/ |title=Saints clinch top seed in NFC, dent Steelers' playoff odds |last=Jones |first=Mike |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref> He set an NFL record for completion percentage (74.4%), breaking his previous record (72.0%) set in {{NFL year|2017}},<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.neworleanssaints.com/news/drew-brees-breaks-own-completion-percentage-record |title=Drew Brees breaks own completion percentage record |date=December 30, 2018 |work=New Orleans Saints |access-date=January 9, 2019}}</ref> and led the league in passer rating (a career high of 115.7). However, with his 3,992 yards, his NFL record streak of 12 consecutive seasons with at least 4,000 passing yards came to an end.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.iberianet.com/sports/saints-choose-rest-over-records/article_c30fbcaa-0c92-11e9-96ec-53881085c125.html |title=Saints choose rest over records |last=Partsch |first=Raymond |date=December 30, 2018 |work=iberianet.com |access-date=January 9, 2019 |publisher=The Daily Iberian}}</ref> He led the league with six fourth quarter comebacks and seven game-winning drives.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2018/passing.htm |title=2018 NFL Passing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#NFC: New Orleans Saints 20, Philadelphia Eagles 14|Divisional Round]] against the [[2018 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], the Saints started badly, quickly falling into a 14\u20130 hole, but recovered and scored 20 unanswered points over the final three quarters to win and advance to their first [[NFC Championship Game]] since their 2009 Super Bowl winning season. Brees completed 28 of 38 passes for 301 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception in the win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2815486-drew-brees-lifts-saints-to-nfc-championship-with-win-vs-nick-foles-eagles |title=Drew Brees Lifts Saints to NFC Championship with Win vs. Nick Foles, Eagles |last=Zucker |first=Joseph |website=Bleacher Report |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401038958 |title=Eagles vs. Saints \u2013 Game Recap \u2013 January 13, 2019 \u2013 ESPN |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#NFC: Los Angeles Rams 26, New Orleans Saints 23 (OT)|NFC Championship]], Brees passed for 249 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception as the Saints lost 26-23 in overtime to the [[2018 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]] following a controversial missed pass interference call on a play that started at the Rams' 13-yard line with 1:49 left in regulation. If called, the penalty could have allowed the Saints to run out most of the clock, due to the Rams having only one timeout remaining, and try a go-ahead field goal that would have likely won the game for New Orleans.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/stevesilverman/2019/01/22/rams-patriots-overtime-victories-make-championship-sunday-one-for-the-ages/ |title=Rams, Patriots Overtime Victories Make Championship Sunday One For The Ages |last=Silverman |first=Steve |date=January 22, 2019 |website=Forbes |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/nfl/2019/1/20/18190891/pass-interference-rams-saints-nickell-robey-coleman |title=Missed pass interference on Rams probably cost Saints a Super Bowl spot |last=Kirshner |first=Alex |date=January 20, 2019 |website=SBNation.com |access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> Brees became the first and only player in NFL history to throw touchdown passes to 15 different players (of which nine were undrafted) in a single season, including the playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/01/20/drew-brees-new-orleans-saints-touchdown-passes-receivers-list |title=Drew Brees throws TD to 15th different receiver this season |website=SI.com |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> He finished second in the MVP voting to [[Patrick Mahomes]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2818883-nfl-mvp-2018-19-award-winner-voting-results-and-twitter-reaction |title=NFL MVP 2018-19: Award Winner, Voting Results and Twitter Reaction |last=Kasabian |first=Paul |date=February 2, 2019 |website=Bleacher Report |language=en |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref> He was ranked as the second best player in the NFL by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2019]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2019/0ap3000001038324/Top-100-Players-of-2019-Drew-Brees-No-2 |title='Top 100 Players of 2019': New Orleans Saints quarterback Drew Brees |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=August 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2019 season====\n{{See also|2019 New Orleans Saints season}}\n[[File:Drew Brees.png|thumb|Brees at the [[2020 Pro Bowl]] ]]\nIn the first game of the season, a ''[[Monday Night Football]]'' match against the [[2019 Houston Texans season|Houston Texans]], Brees threw for 370 yards, two touchdowns, and one interception as the Saints overcame a slow start to win 30\u201328.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128021 |title=Lutz's 58-yard field goal lifts Saints over Texans, 30-28 |date=September 9, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 9, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In the Saints' Week 2 game against the [[2019 Los Angeles Rams season|Los Angeles Rams]], Brees completed 3 of 5 passes for 38 yards and an interception before an injury to his right hand forced him out of the game. The next day, an MRI revealed that Brees had suffered a torn ligament in the thumb of his right hand, which would require surgery and reportedly cause him to miss six to eight weeks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001055668/article/drew-brees-to-have-surgery-on-torn-right-thumb |title=Drew Brees to have surgery on torn right thumb |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=September 16, 2019 |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=September 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001069503/article/drew-brees-thumb-set-to-start-against-cardinals |title=Drew Brees (thumb) set to start against Cardinals |last=Gordon |first=Grant |date=October 26, 2019 |website=NFL.com |access-date=November 10, 2019}}</ref> Brees returned in Week 8 against the [[2019 Arizona Cardinals season|Arizona Cardinals]], finishing with 373 passing yards, three touchdowns, and an interception as the Saints won 31\u20139.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/27943069/drew-brees-throws-3-tds-return-saints-rout-cardinals |title=Brees throws for 3 TDs in return as Saints roll |date=October 27, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=November 10, 2019}}</ref> In Week 11 against the [[2019 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], Brees threw for 228 yards and three touchdowns in the 34\u201317 win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128084 |title=Brees throws for 228 yards, 3 TDs as Saints beat Bucs 34-17 |date=November 17, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 17, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> In Week 12, against the [[2019 Carolina Panthers season|Carolina Panthers]], he passed for 311 yards, three touchdowns, and one interception in the 34\u201331 win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201911240nor.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at New Orleans Saints - November 24th, 2019 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=November 27, 2019}}</ref> In Week 14 against the [[2019 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]], Brees completed 29 of 40 passes for 349 yards, five touchdowns and no interceptions and scored a one-yard rushing touchdown, but his efforts were in vain as the Saints narrowly lost 48\u201346.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127964 |title=Garoppolo's 4 TD passes help 49ers top Saints, 48-46 |date=December 8, 2019 |website=www.espn.com|agency=Associated Press |access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref> During Week 15 against the [[2019 Indianapolis Colts season|Indianapolis Colts]] on ''[[Monday Night Football]]'', Brees broke former Colts quarterback [[Peyton Manning]]'s record for most career touchdowns, throwing his 540th to [[tight end]] [[Josh Hill (American football)|Josh Hill]] on his career-best 20th straight completion in the third quarter.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/saints-drew-brees-sets-nfl-record-for-career-td-passes-on-monday-night-football/ |title=Saints' Drew Brees sets two NFL records in blowout win on 'Monday Night Football' |last=DeArdo |first=Bryan |date=December 16, 2019 |work=CBS Sports |access-date=December 16, 2019}}</ref> Brees's record-breaking touchdown pass was his third touchdown pass on the night. He finished the game with four touchdowns and 304 yards as the Saints defeated the Colts by a 34\u20137 score.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128117 |title=Brees sets NFL all-time TD mark as Saints crush Colts 34-7 |date=December 16, 2019|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 16, 2019}}</ref> In addition, Brees completed 29 of his 30 pass attempts for a career high and NFL single game record 96.7% completion percentage rate, surpassing the previous record (28 out of 29 passes for a 96.6% completion percentage rate) which had been set the previous year by his former Chargers teammate [[Philip Rivers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theringer.com/nfl/2019/12/17/21025732/saints-colts-brees-all-time-touchdown-record-completion-percentage |title=Drew Brees Is Your New Touchdown King, and the Saints Look Scary As Hell |last=Heifetz |first=Danny |date=December 17, 2019 |website=The Ringer |language=en |access-date=December 17, 2019}}</ref> In the following week's game against the [[2019 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], Brees threw for 279 yards and three touchdowns during the 38\u201328 win. During the game, Brees helped wide receiver [[Michael Thomas (wide receiver, born 1993)|Michael Thomas]] break the single season receptions record formerly held by [[Marvin Harrison]] with his 144th catch of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127935 |title=Saints chasing NFC's top seed rally to beat Titans 38-28 |date=December 22, 2019|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 22, 2019}}</ref> In Week 17 against the Carolina Panthers, Brees threw for 253 yards and three touchdowns during the 42\u201310 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127975 |title=Saints take care of Panthers, still hope for playoff bye |date=December 29, 2019|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 29, 2019}}</ref> In the 2019 season, Brees appeared in 11 games and finished with 2,979 passing yards, 27 touchdowns, and four interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/B/BreeDr00/gamelog/2019/ |title=Drew Brees 2019 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref> He finished with a completion percentage of 74.34%, which finished second in NFL history to his record from the previous season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/leaders/pass_cmp_perc_single_season.htm |title=NFL Pass Completion % Single-Season Leaders |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the NFC Wild Card game against the [[2019 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]], Brees threw for 208 yards, one touchdown, and one interception during the 26\u201320 overtime loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401131038 |title=Cook, Vikings upend Saints 26-20 in OT in NFC playoffs |date=January 5, 2020|agency=Associated Press |website=www.espn.com |access-date=January 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====2020 season====\n{{See also|2020 New Orleans Saints season}}\nOn March 17, 2020, Brees signed a two-year, $50 million contract extension with the Saints.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001106597/article/drew-brees-agrees-to-2year-50m-deal-with-saints |title=Drew Brees agrees to 2-year, $50M deal with Saints |last=Patra |first=Kevin |date=March 17, 2020 |website=NFL.com |access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n==NFL career statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n! colspan=\"2\"|Legend\n|-\n| style=\"background:#cfecec; width:3em;\"|\n| Led the league\n|-\n| style=\"background:#E0CEF2; width:3em;\"|\n| NFL record\n|-\n| style=\"background:#afe6ba; width:3em;\"|\n| Won the Super Bowl\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FFD700; width:3em;\"|\n| AP [[NFL Offensive Player of the Year]]\n|-\n| '''Bold'''\n| Career high\n|}\n\n===Regular season===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! G !! GS !! Comp !! Att !! Yds !! Pct !! Avg !! TD !! Int !! Lng !! Ypg !! Sck !! SckY !! Rate\n|-\n! [[2001 NFL season|2001]] !! [[2001 San Diego Chargers season|SD]]\n| 1 || 0 || 15 || 27 || 221 || 55.6 || 8.2 || 1 || 0 || 40 || 221.0 || 2 || 12 || 94.8\n|-\n! [[2002 NFL season|2002]] !! [[2002 San Diego Chargers season|SD]]\n| 16 || 16 || 320 || 526 || 3,284 || 60.8 || 6.2 || 17 || 16 || 52 || 205.3 || 24 || 180\n| 76.9\n|-\n! [[2003 NFL season|2003]] !! [[2003 San Diego Chargers season|SD]]\n| 11 || 11 || 205 || 356 || 2,108 || 57.6 || 5.9 || 11 || 15 || 68 || 191.6 || 21 || 178 || 67.5\n|-\n! [[2004 NFL season|2004]] !! [[2004 San Diego Chargers season|SD]]\n| 15 || 15 || 262 || 400 || 3,159 || 65.5 || 7.9 || 27 || 7 || 79 || 210.6 || 18 || 131 || 104.8\n|-\n! [[2005 NFL season|2005]] !! [[2005 San Diego Chargers season|SD]]\n| 16 || 16 || 323 || 500 || 3,576 || 64.6 || 7.2 || 24 || 15 || 54 || 223.5 || 27 || 223 || 89.2\n|-\n! [[2006 NFL 