 || 73 || 670 || 65.8 || '''9.2''' || 5 || '''3''' || 80 || 335.0 || 3 || 23 || 100.8\n|-\n! [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs|2018]] !! [[2018 New Orleans Saints season|NO]]\n| 2 || 2 || 54 || 78 || 550 || 69.2 || 7.2 || 4 || 2 || 43 || 275.0 || 4 || 25 || 95.6\n|-\n! [[2019\u201320 NFL playoffs|2019]] !! [[2018 New Orleans Saints season|NO]]\n| 1 || 1 || 26 || 33 || 208 || '''78.8''' || 6.3 || 1 || 1 || 20 || 208.0 || 3 || 31 || 90.4\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Career !! 16 !! 16 !! 434 !! 648 !! 4,967 !! 67.0 !! 7.7 !! 34 !! 12 !! 88 !! 310.4 !! 29 !! 206 !! 99.6\n|}\n\n==Career awards and records==\n{{main|List of career achievements by Drew Brees}}\nBrees has earned several awards in both college and the NFL, including:\n* [[Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award|Super Bowl MVP]] ([[Super Bowl XLIV|XLIV]])\n* 13\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2005 Pro Bowl|2004]], [[2007 Pro Bowl|2006]], [[2009 Pro Bowl|2008]]\u2013[[2015 Pro Bowl|2014]], [[2017 Pro Bowl|2016]]\u2013[[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* First-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2006 All-Pro Team|2006]]) \n* 4\u00d7 Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2008 All-Pro Team|2008]], [[2009 All-Pro Team|2009]], [[2011 All-Pro Team|2011]], [[2018 All-Pro Team|2018]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[National Football League Offensive Player of the Year Award|NFL Offensive Player of the Year]] (2008, 2011)\n* [[Sports Illustrated Sportsman of the Year|''Sports Illustrated'' Sportsman of the Year]] (2010)\n* [[Associated Press Male Athlete of the Year]] (2010)\n* [[Bert Bell Award]] (2009)\n* [[Walter Payton Man of the Year Award|Walter Payton NFL Man of the Year]] (2006)\n* [[National Football League Comeback Player of the Year Award|NFL Comeback Player of the Year]] (2004)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2000)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Big Ten Conference football individual awards|Big Ten Offensive Player of the Year]] (1998, 2000)\n\nMajor NFL records held by Brees include:\n* Most career regular season passing touchdowns: [[List of National Football League career passing touchdowns leaders|547]]\n* [[List of National Football League passing yards leaders|Most career passing yards]] \n* [[List of National Football League career passing completions leaders|Most career pass completions]]\n* Most pass completions in a season\n* Highest career completion percentage\n* Highest single-season completion percentage\n* Highest single-game completion percentage\n* [[List of NFL quarterbacks with seven touchdown passes in a game|Most touchdown passes in a game]] (tied)\n* [[List of most consecutive games with touchdown passes in the National Football League|Most consecutive games with a touchdown pass]]\n\n==Personal life==\nBrees married his college sweetheart Brittany Dudchenko in February 2003.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Wickersham |first=Seth |date=October 16, 2002 |title=Secrets of the Ya-Ya Brotherhood |url=http://assets.espn.go.com/magazine/wickersham_20021016.html |magazine=[[ESPN The Magazine]] |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> The couple have four children together; three sons born January 2009,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/nfl/story/2009-01-29/saints-qb-enjoys-life-new-dad |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120910163119/http://aol.sportingnews.com/nfl/story/2009-01-29/saints-qb-enjoys-life-new-dad |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 10, 2012 |title=Saints QB enjoys life as new dad - NFL - Sporting News |date=September 10, 2012 |website=archive.is |access-date=August 17, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> October 2010,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://people.com/parents/drew-brees-welcomes-son-bowen-christopher/ |title=Drew Brees Welcomes Son Bowen Christopher |authors=''People'' Staff |date=October 20, 2010 |website=People |access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref> and August 2012,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2012/08/drew_brittany_brees_announce_b.html |title=Drew, Brittany Brees announce birth of their third son, Callen Christian Brees |last=Tatum |first=Doug |date=August 16, 2012 |website=NOLA |access-date=February 4, 2019}}</ref> and a daughter in August 2014.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.wdsu.com/news/local-news/new-orleans/drew-brees-welcomes-baby-girl-posts-photo-of-daughter-to-social-media/27733874#ixzz3BZPp0VTO |title=Drew Brees welcomes baby girl, posts photo of daughter to social media |last=Rousseau |first=Randi |date=August 26, 2014 |access-date=March 15, 2019 |publisher=[[WDSU]]}}</ref>\n[[File:Drew Brees announces the Saints' draft pick at the NFL 2010 Draft.jpg|thumb|right|Brees announcing the Saints' draft pick at the [[2010 NFL Draft]]]]\nBrees moved to [[New Orleans]] not long after the devastation of [[Hurricane Katrina]].<ref name=\"NewmanE\">{{Cite journal |last=Newman |first=E |date=2006 |title=Drew Brees |url=http://eds.b.ebscohost.com.libezp.lib.lsu.edu/eds/detail/detail?sid=220aabd0-c0dc-4e3b-be97-0f4ac621627f%40sessionmgr111&vid=0&hid=127&bdata=JnNpdGU9ZWRzLWxpdmUmc2NvcGU9c2l0ZQ%3d%3d#db=s3h&AN=22256409 |journal=Sports Illustrated |volume=105 |issue=10 |page=34 |access-date=February 25, 2015}}</ref> He admits that it was tough moving to a city that was still in shambles from the hurricane; however, he and Brittany immediately fell in love with the culture and \"soul\" of the city.<ref name=NewmanE /> They purchased and renovated a home in [[Uptown New Orleans]], where they still live.<ref name=\"uptown\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2013/05/saints_in_the_city_column.html |title=Some New Orleans Saints can't resist lure of life in the big city |last=Duncan |first=Jeff |date=May 30, 2013 |work=[[The Times-Picayune]] |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> Brees admits in an interview that he thinks his family is now completed especially because three boys and one girl were always the couple's dream.<ref name=\"Holder\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nola.com/sports/saints/article_34988d66-5a91-590a-9891-02dd6729dfc4.html |title=New Orleans Saints' Drew Brees Announces Birth of fourth child, the family's first girl |last=Holder |first=Larry |date=August 26, 2014 |website=NOLA |publisher=The Times Picayune |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> All four children were born in New Orleans and are being raised there.<ref name=\"Holder\" /> The four priorities in Brees' life are faith, family, football, and philanthropy; otherwise known as the \"four F's\" by Brees.<ref name=LaydenT /> Brees maintains his offseason home in San Diego.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://blog.sfgate.com/49ers/2012/01/11/49ers-connection-to-drew-brees-and-darren-sproles |title=49ers connection to Brees and Darren Sproles |last=Lynch |first=Kevin |date=January 11, 2012 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle|blog.sfgate.com]] |access-date=January 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBrees was raised as a [[Christianity|Christian]] but stated that he only became committed at age 17 when he was at church with a [[Anterior cruciate ligament injury|torn ACL]] and was wondering who he was and what his purpose was in life.<ref name=\"SI2010\" /> Brees later faced other trials such as tearing his shoulder in 2005; however, he maintains that these setbacks only strengthened his relationship with God.<ref name=LaydenT /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www1.cbn.com/700club/drew-brees-saint-new-orleans |title=Drew Brees: The Saint of New Orleans |date=April 24, 2012 |website=The Christian Broadcasting Network |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nA [[birthmark]] on the right side of his face led to [[bullying]] when he was young.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.distractify.com/p/what-happened-to-drew-brees-face |title=What Happened to Drew Brees' Face? Here's Why the Saints Quarterback Has a Scar |first=Samantha |last=Faragalli Younghans |website=distractify.com |date=2019 |accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn July 6, 2010, Brees released his first book,<ref name=\"ABC2010\" /> entitled ''Coming Back Stronger: Unleashing the Hidden Power of Adversity'', co-authored by Chris Fabry.<ref>Drew Brees with Chris Fabry, ''Coming Back Stronger: Unleashing the Hidden Power of Adversity'' ([[Tyndale House]] Publishers, 2010), {{ISBN|978-1-4143-3943-6}}. [https://books.google.com/books?id=lez8urgN7IsC Excerpts available] at [[Google Books]].</ref> ''Coming Back Stronger'' opened at number 3 on the nonfiction [[The New York Times Best Seller list|bestseller list]] of ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hardcover Nonfiction Books - Best Sellers - July 25, 2010 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2010/07/25/hardcover-nonfiction/ |website=The New York Times |accessdate=January 5, 2020 |date=July 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nola.com/sports/saints/article_abf808f0-8009-5642-927f-949a8a02af30.html |title=Drew Brees' book will debut at No. 3 on the New York Times best sellers list |website=NOLA.com |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBrees' mother, Mina Brees, died on August 7, 2009, aged 59, from a prescription drug overdose.<ref name=LaydenT /> The death was ruled a suicide.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.statesman.com/blogs/content/shared-gen/blogs/austin/blotter/entries/2009/11/16/mina_brees_death_ruled_suicide.html |title=Mina Brees\u2019 death ruled suicide |date=November 16, 2009 |publisher=Statesman.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091118225918/http://www.statesman.com/blogs/content/shared-gen/blogs/austin/blotter/entries/2009/11/16/mina_brees_death_ruled_suicide.html |archive-date=November 18, 2009 |access-date=May 11, 2011}}</ref> Brees was briefly excused from training camp for a \"family matter\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://nfl.fanhouse.com/2009/08/09/drew-brees-mother-dies-saints-qb-excused-from-training-camp? |title=Drew Brees' Mother Dies, Saints QB Excused From Training Camp |last=Herrera |first=Tom |date=August 9, 2009 |website=nfl.fanhouse.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090811003511/http://nfl.fanhouse.com/2009/08/09/drew-brees-mother-dies-saints-qb-excused-from-training-camp/ |archive-date=August 11, 2009 |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> In 2006, Brees described their relationship as \"nonexistent\" ever since he refused to hire his mother as his agent when he entered the NFL.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2644387 |title=Brees wants no part of mom's campaign in Texas |date=October 31, 2006 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=August 17, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Drew Brees mother dies in Colorado |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/football/nfl/08/10/brees.ap/index.html |website=SI.com |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=August 10, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813135710/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/football/nfl/08/10/brees.ap/index.html |archivedate=August 13, 2009 |date=August 10, 2009}}</ref> After her death, Brees stated that this quote was three years old and that his relationship with his mother had been improving.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news?slug=jc-saintscamp081109&prov=yhoo&type=lgns |title=Mom\u2019s death makes Brees blink, but focus remains |last=Cole |first=Jason |website=Yahoo! Sports |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814024043/https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news?slug=jc-saintscamp081109&prov=yhoo&type=lgns |archive-date=August 14, 2009 |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> In his autobiography, released almost a year later, he wrote that their relationship had been on the mend<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/09000d5d81901746/article/brees-hopes-memoir-will-help-inspire-others-who-face-adversity |title=Brees hopes memoir will help inspire others who face adversity |date=July 6, 2010 |access-date=August 17, 2019 |publisher=[[National Football League|NFL]] |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> and that she had been looking forward to her meeting his son; her first grandchild.\n\nIn April 2010, Brees was voted by fans as the cover athlete of [[EA Sports]] ''[[Madden NFL 11]]'' [[video game]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=5125018 |title=Fans pick Brees for cover of Madden 11 game |date=April 22, 2010 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=June 26, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nBrees wears #9 on his uniform in honor of late baseball player [[Ted Williams]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://fifthdown.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/01/29/30-seconds-with-drew-brees |title=30 Seconds with Saints Quarterback Drew Brees |last=Mallozzi |first=Vincent M. |date=January 29, 2011 |work=New York Times |access-date=November 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBrees is sometimes known by the nicknames \"Breesus\" by Saints fans<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2009/nov/30/brees-a-godsend-for-saints |title=Brees a godsend for Saints |last=Leonard |first=Tod |date=November 30, 2009 |work=[[San Diego Union-Tribune]] |access-date=December 9, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091203080017/http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2009/nov/30/brees-a-godsend-for-saints/ |archive-date=December 3, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nola.com/fashion/index.ssf/2009/11/post_3.html |title=New Orleans Saints fans get creative: What Who Dats are wearing |last=Langenhennig |first=Susan |date=November 30, 2009 |work=[[Times-Picayune]] |access-date=December 9, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2009/11/breesus_is_the_reason_for_the.html |title=Breesus' is the reason for potentially perfect season |last=Duncan |first=Jeff |date=November 2, 2009 |work=[[Times-Picayune]] |access-date=December 9, 2009}}</ref> and \"Cool Brees\", which he acquired during his younger years for his calmness under pressure.<ref name=\"BaltimoreSun\" /><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/magazine/archives/news/story?page=magazine-20010416-article58 |title='COOL BREES' IGNITED PURDUE, BUT CAN HE GENERATE ENOUGH HEAT TO BURN UP THE NFL? |last=Broder |first=John |date=July 10, 2012 |publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, 2010, Brees became the national spokesperson for [[AdvoCare|AdvoCare International]],<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.advocare.com/company/news/news_20100305.aspx |title=AdvoCare and NFL World Champion Drew Brees Take Relationship to the Next Level |date=March 30, 2010 |access-date=November 14, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204090838/http://www.advocare.com/company/news/news_20100305.aspx |archive-date=December 4, 2010 |publisher=Advocare Press Release}}</ref> a [[multi-level marketing]] company,<ref name=\"ppcomp\">{{cite web |title=AdvoCare Policies, Procedures, and the Compensation Plan |url=https://www.advocare.com/0908345/Pdf/policy.pdf |website=advocare.com |accessdate=May 11, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009052537/https://www.advocare.com/0908345/Pdf/policy.pdf |archivedate=October 9, 2011}}</ref> which produces weight management, nutritional supplement, and personal care products.\n\n[[File:Drew Brees Kuwait 2.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Brees visiting U.S. soldiers in [[Kuwait]], April 2007]]\nBrees owns a variety of restaurant businesses. In May 2015, he purchased a 25% stake in \"Walk-On's Bistreaux & Bar\", a sports bar that originated in Baton Rouge and is currently expanding their franchising into other Gulf Coast states. In 2019, he opened a Walk-On's restaurant in [[Midland, Texas]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mrt.com/entertainment/restaurants-bars/article/NFL-QB-Drew-Brees-breaks-ground-on-Midland-13834239.php |title=NFL QB Drew Brees breaks ground on Midland restaurant location |last=Lopez |first=Rich |date=May 10, 2019 |website=Midland Reporter-Telegram |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref> During initial talks with Walk-On's, Brees said that he was interested in bringing over some of the lessons that he had learned as a [[Jimmy John's]] franchise owner. He currently owns nine Jimmy John's stores with a tenth under construction {{as of|2019|August|lc=y}}.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.franchisetimes.com/September-2016/Saints-QB-Drew-Brees-suits-up-for-his-next-franchise-gig/ |title=Saints QB Drew Brees suits up for his next franchise gig |last=Kaiser |first=Tom |date=August 25, 2016 |publisher=[[Franchise Times]] |access-date=February 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.aol.com/article/finance/2019/08/20/jimmy-johns-and-superfan-turned-franchisee-drew-brees-want-to-buy-you-a-house-seriously/23797781/ |title=Jimmy John's and superfan-turned-franchisee Drew Brees want to buy you a house \u2013 seriously |website=AOL.com |language=en |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref> Carl Buergler, Jimmy John's director of operations, played football at Purdue with Brees.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nola.com/saints/index.ssf/2014/06/drew_brees_commits_to_having_2.html |title=Drew Brees plans to open several more Jimmy John's sandwich shops in New Orleans region, magazine reports |last=Dabe |first=Christopher |date=June 10, 2014 |website=NOLA.com |access-date=March 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhen Brees broke the NFL record for all-time passing yards, he sent a personalized football and letter to those players that helped him reach the milestone.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ftw/2018/12/14/drew-brees-classy-gift-teammates-coaches-helped-set-passing-record/38739623/ |title=Drew Brees sends classy gift to teammates who helped him break NFL record |last=Schwartz |first=Nick |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=August 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nBrees utilizes former Major League Baseball player and coach [[Tom House]] as his mechanics coach.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2019/08/05/training-camp-drew-brees-saints-patrick-mahomes-chiefs-tom-brady-patriots |title=Drew Brees, at 40, Is Looking To Get Better |last=Breer |first=Albert |website=SI.com |language=en |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2019/08/quarterback-gurus-job-title-is-stupid |title=Don't call them gurus: How private QB coaches are changing football |last=McKenna |first=Henry |date=August 22, 2019 |website=For The Win |language=en |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Brees partnered with San Diego Surf Sports to help with the local youth sports scene in the San Diego area.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ranchosantafereview.com/sports/story/2019-08-02/san-diego-surf-sports-partnership-with-nfl-star-drew-brees-portends-expansive-role-for-storied-soccer-club |title=San Diego Surf Sports partnership with NFL star Drew Brees portends expansive role for storied soccer club |date=August 2, 2019 |website=Rancho Santa Fe Review |language=en-US |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe is a Republican.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://voterrecords.com/voter/84106902/drew-brees |title=Drew Christopher Brees from New Orleans, Louisiana |website=VoterRecords.com |access-date=November 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Charity and volunteer activities==\nIn 2010, ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' described Brees as \"an athlete as adored and appreciated as any in an American city today\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1164811/3/index.htm |title=The Heart Of New Orleans: He's been the NFL's most prolific quarterback over the past four years, but to the city that has adopted him, Drew Brees is much more \u2013 a driving force in the ongoing effort to rebuild and renew |last=King |first=Peter |date=January 18, 2010 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |access-date=January 15, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116052045/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1164811/3/index.htm |archive-date=January 16, 2010}}</ref> When ''Sports Illustrated'' selected him for the 2010 [[Sports Illustrated Sportsperson of the Year|Sportsman of the Year]] award, it said the award was \"[f]or not only leading the New Orleans Saints to the first Super Bowl title in the franchise's history, but also for helping lead the city of New Orleans' rebirth after the tragedy of Hurricane Katrina\". The fact that he and his family lived in New Orleans proper, instead of the suburbs like many players did, further endeared him to fans.<ref name=\"SOY\" /><ref name=\"uptown\" />\n\n===Brees Dream Foundation===\nIn 2003, Brees and his wife, Brittany, founded the Brees Dream Foundation to support cancer patients and research in memory of Brittany's aunt who died of cancer. Since Brees' move to New Orleans, the foundation has expanded to provide assistance for [[Hurricane Katrina]] rebuilding projects. The foundation continues to fund and support various programs in [[San Diego]], [[California]], where Brees usually spends his offseasons, and [[West Lafayette, Indiana]], where the couple's [[alma mater]], Purdue, is located and where Brees returns to visit yearly.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.purdueexponent.org/campus/article_e31c6dec-53ba-5893-ae79-42a6274b9caa.html |title=Drew Brees' foundation makes donation to Purdue organization |last=Schmidt |first=Jake |date=June 28, 2013 |access-date=March 15, 2019 |publisher=[[Purdue Exponent]]}}</ref>\n\nBrees and his foundation have been heavily involved in [[Reconstruction of New Orleans|Hurricane Katrina recovery]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=nfl&id=2730727 |title=Brees has New Orleans howling |date=January 14, 2007 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=February 22, 2007 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Drew and Brittany's Brees Dream Foundation announced a partnership<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/13/sports/football/13brees.html |title=A Saint in the City: No Off-Season as Brees Helps New Orleans Rebuild |date=May 13, 2007 |work=The New York Times |access-date=December 19, 2007 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/saints/2007-07-05-sw-drew-brees_N.htm |title=Brees Becomes Patron Saint of New Orleans |last=Corbett |first=Jim |date=July 6, 2007 |work=USA Today |access-date=December 19, 2007}}</ref> in 2007 with international children's charity [[Operation Kids]], to rebuild and restore and recreate academic and athletic facilities, parks, and playgrounds, after-school programs, mentoring programs for the intellectually disabled, neighborhood revitalization projects and child care facilities in [[New Orleans]]. Brees also sponsors the Rebuilding Through Brotherhood program to invite fellow Sigma Chi members to the New Orleans community to build homes with the [[Habitat for Humanity]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.drewbrees.com/foundation_programs/rebuilding-through-brotherhood/ |title=Rebuilding Through Brotherhood |website=drewbrees.com |language=en-US |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211010625/http://www.drewbrees.com/foundation_programs/rebuilding-through-brotherhood/ |archive-date=December 11, 2018 |access-date=December 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Other activities===\n[[File:Football players visit Guantanamo.jpg|thumb|Brees signs autographs at [[Guantanamo Bay Naval Base]] on June 29, 2009, along with fellow NFL players [[Billy Miller (American football)|Billy Miller]] and [[Donnie Edwards]].]]\n\nBrees has been on multiple [[United Service Organizations|USO]] tours throughout his career. In late June 2009, he visited the [[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]]. Following his return, Brees was quoted as stating that Guantanamo captives were being treated ten times better than convicts in U.S. prisons.<ref name=\"SportsRadio2009-07-30\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.xxsportsradio.com/pages/landing?Transcript-of-Drew-Brees-Interview-709=1&blockID=63805&feedID=2904 |title=Transcript of Drew Brees Interview: Scott and BR Interview with Drew Brees On Guantanamo Bay |date=July 9, 2009 |access-date=August 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.xxsportsradio.com%2Fpages%2Flanding%3FTranscript-of-Drew-Brees-Interview-709%3D1%26blockID%3D63805%26feedID%3D2904&date=2009-08-03 |archive-date=August 3, 2009 |publisher=[[Sports Radio]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Nola\">{{Cite news |url=http://blog.nola.com/jeffduncan/2009/07/_drew_brees_is_a.html |title=Drew Brees raises eyebrows with comments about Guantanamo Bay |last=Duncan |first=Jeff |date=July 30, 2009 |access-date=July 30, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090730015234/http://blog.nola.com/jeffduncan/2009/07/_drew_brees_is_a.html |archive-date=July 30, 2009 |publisher=NOLA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://content.usatoday.com/topics/post/People/Athletes/NFL/Drew+Brees/68494164.blog/1 |title=Drew Brees weighs in on his trip to Gitmo |last=Weir |first=Tom |date=July 10, 2009 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=August 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fcontent.usatoday.com%2Ftopics%2Fpost%2FPeople%2FAthletes%2FNFL%2FDrew%2BBrees%2F68494164.blog%2F1&date=2009-08-03 |archive-date=August 3, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"YahooBreesGuantanamo\">{{Cite news |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/blog/shutdown_corner/post/Brees-says-Guantanamo-Bay-inmates-are-having-a-g?urn=nfl,179844 |title=Guantanamo Bay inmates are having a grand time, says Drew Brees |date=July 30, 2009 |access-date=July 30, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090803064323/http://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/blog/shutdown_corner/post/Brees-says-Guantanamo-Bay-inmates-are-having-a-g?urn=nfl%2C179844 |archive-date=August 3, 2009 |publisher=[[Yahoo News]]/[[Yahoo Sports]]}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, Brees signed a promotional deal with [[Chili's|Chili's Grill & Bar]] to promote the chain's new line of hamburgers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/superbowl/2008/01/31/soundbites-drew-brees/ |title=Great Moments in Marketing: Drew Brees |last=Kirschenbaum |first=Jill |date=January 31, 2008 |website=WSJ |language=en-US |access-date=August 17, 2019}}</ref> The promotion helped raise money for charity. In June 2008, Brees participated in the Pro Sports Team Challenge, a competition for professional athletes to help raise money for charities. The charity Brees played for was [[Operation Kids]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.operationkids.com |title=Operation Kids: Until Every Child Is OK |website=Operationkids.com |access-date=November 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn February 18, 2007, Brees was honored by the [[Krewe of Bacchus]], a New Orleans [[Mardi Gras]] parade organization, as the 2007 Grand Marshal of the Bacchus parade.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.nola.com/mardigras/index.ssf/2009/12/saints_quarterback_drew_brees.html |title=New Orleans Saints quarterback Drew Brees to reign as Bacchus during 2009 Carnival |last=Krupa |first=Michelle |date=December 12, 2009 |work=NOLA.com |access-date=January 15, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091214162227/https://www.nola.com/mardigras/index.ssf/2009/12/saints_quarterback_drew_brees.html |archive-date=December 14, 2009 |publisher=[[Times-Picayune]]}}</ref> Brees presided as Bacchus XLII for the 2010 parade on February 14, 2010, one week after the Super Bowl during Mardi Gras season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/01/24/sports/football/24saints.html |title=Thriving Saints Helped New Orleans Revive After Hurricane Katrina |last=Lapointe |first=Joe |date=January 23, 2010 |website=The New York Times |language=en-US |access-date=August 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2010, President Obama appointed Brees to be co-chair of the newly renamed [[President's Council on Fitness, Sports and Nutrition]], along with former Olympic gymnast [[Dominique Dawes]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2010/06/michelle-obama-jumps-rope-emphasizes-nutrition-/1 |title=Michelle Obama jumps rope, emphasizes nutrition |last=Oldenburg |first=Ann |date=June 24, 2010 |website=USATODAY.COM |access-date=February 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=First Lady Launches President\u2019s Council on Fitness, Sports and Nutrition |url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/first-lady-launches-president-s-council-fitness-sports-and-nutrition |website=whitehouse.gov |accessdate=January 5, 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216153520/https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/first-lady-launches-president-s-council-fitness-sports-and-nutrition |archivedate=February 16, 2017 |date=June 23, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2010, Brees appeared in an [[It Gets Better]] video, in which he gave an anti-bullying message in the wake of a series of suicides committed by gay teenagers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2010/10/16/drew-brees-stands-up-to-bullies |title=Drew Brees stands up to bullies |last=Florio |first=Mike |date=October 16, 2010 |publisher=Profootballtalk.nbcsports.com |access-date=May 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Brees filed a lawsuit against a San Diego jeweler. The lawsuit claims Brees and his wife paid $15 million for investment-grade diamonds that an independent appraiser valued at only $6 million.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cbs8.com/clip/14246877/saints-qb-drew-brees-sues-over-millions-spent-at-san-diego-jewelry-store |title=Saints QB Drew Brees sues over millions spent at San Diego jewelry store |date=April 3, 2018 |website=www.cbs8.com |language=en |access-date=February 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/drew-brees-lawsuit-jeweler-alleged-diamond-fraud-2018-6 |title=Drew Brees is suing a jeweler for $9 million, saying he was overcharged by millions for diamonds |last=Hoffower |first=Hillary |date=June 29, 2018 |website=Business Insider |access-date=February 20, 2019}}</ref> On June 21, 2019, Brees was awarded $6 million in the lawsuit.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/sports/drew-brees-awarded-6-million-in-diamond-fraud-lawsuit |title=NFL QB Drew Brees awarded $6M in diamond fraud lawsuit |last=Stimson |first=Brie |date=June 22, 2019 |website=Fox News |language=en-US |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, Brees partnered with Brandon Landry, co-founder of Walk-On's, launching a new restaurant.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.businessreport.com/business/walk-ons-founder-brandon-landry-drew-brees-to-launch-new-restaurant-brand |title=Walk-On's founder Brandon Landry, Drew Brees to launch new restaurant brand |last=Duchman |first=Holly |date=March 13, 2019 |website=Greater Baton Rouge Business Report |access-date=June 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of NCAA major college football yearly total offense leaders]]\n* [[List of gridiron football quarterbacks passing statistics]]\n* [[List of most consecutive games with touchdown passes in the National Football League]]\n* [[List of most consecutive starts by a National Football League quarterback]]\n* [[List of National Football League career passer rating leaders]]\n* [[List of National Football League career passing completions leaders]]\n* [[List of National Football League career passing touchdowns leaders]]\n* [[List of National Football League career passing yards leaders]]\n* [[List of National Football League career quarterback wins leaders]]\n* [[List of National Football League quarterback playoff records]]\n* [[List of NFL quarterbacks who have passed for 500 or more yards in a game]]\n* [[List of NFL quarterbacks who have posted a perfect passer rating]]\n* [[List of NFL quarterbacks with 5,000 passing yards in a season]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Footballstats|nfl=2504775|espn=2580|cbs=|yahoo=5479|fox=|si=5479|pfr=BreeDr00|rotoworld=591}}\n* [http://www.drewbrees.com The Brees Dream Foundation website]\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20180411190603/http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/brees_drew00.html Purdue Boilermakers profile]\n* [http://www.neworleanssaints.com/team/roster/Drew-Brees/09634fe8-9ab7-4f47-a5ea-c0fb5ad343a9 New Orleans Saints profile]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|rec}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Johnny Unitas]] | title = Consecutive games with a touchdown pass | years = 2012 | after = Incumbent}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Dan Marino]] | title = Most passing yards in a season | years = 2011\u20132013 | after = [[Peyton Manning]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{New Orleans Saints roster navbox}}\n{{NFL starting quarterbacks navbox}}\n{{Navboxes| title = Drew Brees\u2014awards, championships, and honors| list1 =\n{{Purdue Boilermakers quarterback navbox}}\n{{Maxwell Award Winners}}\n{{Chicago Tribune Silver Football navbox}}\n{{Football Academic All-America of the Year}}\n{{Chargers2001DraftPicks}}\n{{San Diego Chargers starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{New Orleans Saints starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{AP NFL Comeback Player}}\n{{Walter Payton Man of the Year Award}}\n{{AP Offensive Players of the Year}}\n{{Bert Bell Award}}\n{{Bart Starr Award}}\n{{\"Whizzer\" White NFL Man of the Year}}\n{{Super Bowl XLIV}}\n{{Super Bowl Champion quarterbacks}}\n{{Super Bowl MVPs}}\n{{FedEx NFL Players}}\n{{Art Rooney Award}}\n{{NFL passing yardage leaders}}\n{{NFL passing touchdown leaders}}\n{{NFL passer rating leaders}}\n{{NFL Quarterbacks with a Perfect Passer Rating}}\n{{Associated Press Male Athlete of the Year navbox}}\n{{SI Sportsman of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brees, Drew}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:People associated with direct selling]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:Purdue Boilermakers football players]]\n[[Category:San Diego Chargers players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl MVPs]]\n[[Category:Unconferenced Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Westlake High School (Texas) alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Thed2333", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRegular season", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drew_Brees"}
{"title_page": "2013\u201314 Coventry City F.C. season", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n| club               = Coventry City\n| season             = 2013\u201314\n| chairman           = Tim Fisher\n| manager            = [[Steven Pressley]]\n| stadium            = [[Sixfields Stadium]]\n| league             = [[2013\u201314 Football League One|League One]]\n| league result      = 18th\n| cup1               = [[2013\u201314 FA Cup|FA Cup]]\n| cup1 result        = Fourth round<br />vs [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| cup2               = [[2013\u201314 Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n| cup2 result        = First round<br />vs [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]]\n| cup3               = [[2013\u201314 Football League Trophy|Football League Trophy]]\n| cup3 result        = Second round<br />vs [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]]\n| league topscorer   = [[Callum Wilson (English footballer)|Callum Wilson]] '''21'''\n| season topscorer   = [[Callum Wilson (English footballer)|Callum Wilson]] '''22'''\n| highest attendance = 4,905 vs [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] \u2013 [[Football League One]] \u2013 26 December 2013\n| lowest attendance  = 1,214 vs [[Hartlepool United F.C.|Hartlepool United]] \u2013 [[FA Cup]] \u2013 17 December 2013\n| average attendance = 2,287\n<!-- Home Kit -->\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1  = _coventry1315h\n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_sh1 = _blue stripes\n| pattern_so1 = _navyline\n| leftarm1    = 87DDEF\n| body1       = \n| rightarm1   = 87DDEF\n| shorts1     = 87DDEF\n| socks1      = 87DDEF\n<!-- Away Kit -->\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = _reading1213a\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = _white stripes\n| pattern_so2 = _greenline\n| leftarm2    = FFDF00\n| body2       = FFDF00\n| rightarm2   = FFDF00\n| shorts2     = 0000FF\n| socks2      = FFFFFF\n| prevseason  = [[2012\u201313 Coventry City F.C. season|2012\u201313]]\n| nextseason  = [[2014\u201315 Coventry City F.C. season|2014\u201315]]\n}}\n\nThe 2013\u201314 season is [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City's]] 94th season in [[The Football League]] and their second consecutive season in [[Football League One|League One]]. In addition to League One, the Sky Blues will also enter the [[Football League Cup]] and [[FA Cup]] in the first rounds. They also enter the [[Football League Trophy]] in the second round after being awarded a bye for the first round.\n\n==Review and events==\n\n===Monthly events===\nThis is a list of the significant events to occur at the club during the 2013\u201314 season, presented in chronological order. This list does not include transfers or match results.\n\n'''June''':\n* 17 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] were drawn to play [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] away in the first round of the [[Football League Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |title=City get Orient in Capital One Cup |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/capital-one-cup-r1-draw-1314-869123.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=17 June 2013}}</ref>\n* 19 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City's]] 2013\u201314 season fixtures in [[Football League One|League One]] were revealed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fixture List |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/fixtures-results/fixtures-list/ |work=CCFC Official Site|date=19 June 2013}}</ref>\n* 28 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] defender [[Aaron Phillips]] pens a new one-year deal with the club, commencing on 1 July 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=City defender pens new deal |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/city-defender-pens-new-deal-885283.aspx? |work=CCFC Official site |date=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n* 28 \u2013 [[Callum Wilson (English footballer)|Callum Wilson]] and [[Billy Daniels (footballer)|Billy Daniels]] have penned new deals at the club. Wilson has penned a one-year deal and Daniels a two-year deal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wilson and Daniels seal City deals |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/wilson-and-daniels-seal-city-deals-886032.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n* 28 \u2013 [[Leon Lobjoit]], Ben Maund, [[Louis Garner]] and Lewis Rankin all sign one-year professional deals at the club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Four pen pro deals |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/four-scholars-sign-885983.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''July''':\n* 3 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] have agreed to groundshare with [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] at the [[Sixfields Stadium]] for the next three years.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coventry City agree groundshare with Northampton Town |url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/exclusive-coventry-city-agree-groundshare-4866094 |work=[[Coventry Telegraph]] |date=3 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 4 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] were awarded a bye for the first round of the [[2013\u201314 Football League Trophy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=City awarded bye for JPT first round |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/city-awarded-bye-for-jpt-first-round-894977.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=4 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 8 \u2013 [[The Football League]] has approved the application from Otium Entertainment Group to see [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] groundshare with [[Northampton Town F.C.|Northampton Town]] to play at [[Sixfields Stadium]] for an initial period of three seasons.<ref>{{cite web |title=Football League statement |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/fl-statement-080713-901919.aspx |work=CCFC Official Site |date=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 10 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]'s second pre-season friendly and first on the tour of the [[Netherlands]] against [[Go Ahead Eagles]] has been cancelled due to the high risk of football hooliganism.<ref>{{cite web |title=Go Ahead Eagles tie cancelled |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/go-ahead-eagles-cancelled-908925.aspx |work=CCFC Official Site |date=11 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 15 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] confirmed a replacement pre-season fixture to replace the cancelled match against [[Go Ahead Eagles]], The Sky Blues would take on German side [[TSV Wachtendonk]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Replacement tour fixture confirmed |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/replacement-tour-fixture-914304.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=15 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 16 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]'s home [[Football League One]] clash against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] has been selected to be shown live on [[Sky Sports]] on Sunday 13 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sheffield United clash on TV |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/sheff-utd-h-televised-919218.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=16 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''August''':\n* 2 \u2013 Otium Entertainment Group were awarded the Golden Share for the [[2013\u201314 in English football|2013\u201314 season]] but club handed ten-point deduction from the [[Football League]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Otium awarded Golden Share |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/statement-on-sanctions-964434.aspx |work=CCFC Official Site |date=2 August 2013}}</ref>\n* 15 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] scooped up the '''LMA Performance of the Week''' award for the 5\u20134 win over [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]].<ref name=\"City win LMA award for win over Bristol\">{{cite web |title=City win LMA award for win over Bristol |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/lma-performance-of-the-week-v-bristol-993042.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=15 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''September''':\n* 3 \u2013 [[Cyrus Christie]] was named '''London Supporters Club Player of the Month'''.<ref name=\"Christie Takes London Vote\">{{cite web |title=Christie Takes London Vote |url=http://www.coventrycity-mad.co.uk/news/tmnw/christie_takes_london_vote_805673/index.shtml? |work=CoventryCityMad |date=3 September 2013}}</ref>\n* 12 \u2013 [[Callum Wilson (English footballer)|Callum Wilson]] won the August goal of the month award for his second of two goals in the 4\u20134 draw with [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] on 25 August 2013.<ref name=\"August Goal of the Month\">{{cite web |title=Wilson wins August Goal of the Month |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/august-goal-of-the-month-winner-1048998.aspx |work=CCFC Official Site |date=12 September 2013}}</ref>\n* 13 \u2013 [[Jordan Willis (footballer)|Jordan Willis]] signed a new two-year contract, with an option of a further year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Willis signs new two-year deal |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/willis-signs-new-deal-1050529.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=13 September 2013}}</ref>\n* 16 \u2013 [[Jordan Clarke (footballer)|Jordan Clarke]] signed a new two-year contract, with an option of a further year.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jordan Clarke signs new contract |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/jordan-clarke-contract-1057616.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=16 September 2013}}</ref>\n* 18 \u2013 [[Callum Wilson (English footballer)|Callum Wilson]] won the August player of the month.<ref name=\"Wilson wins August Player of the Month\">{{cite web |title=Wilson wins August Player of the Month |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/wilson-wins-august-player-of-the-month-1062647.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=18 September 2013}}</ref>\n* 19 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] have teamed up with medical charity Grace Research Fund who will adorn Sky Blues shirts for the next three months.<ref>{{cite web |title=City charity to be shirt sponsor |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/kit-sponsor-1314-1063458.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=19 September 2013}}</ref>\n* 19 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] will wear the new 2013/14 home shirt for the first time for the [[Football League One|League One]] clash against [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]] on 13 October 2013. The match will also be shown live on [[Sky Sports]].<ref>{{cite web |title=City to wear new kit against Blades |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/new-kit-to-be-worn-1064362.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=19 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''October''':\n* 4 \u2013 [[Steven Pressley]] handed a first team squad number to 16-year-old academy player [[James Maddison]].<ref>{{cite web |title=City youngster brought into squad |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/maddison-squad-number-1095147.aspx |work=CCFC Official Site |date=4 October 2013}}</ref>\n* 16 \u2013 [[Franck Moussa]] won the September goal of the month award for his long-range effort in the 3\u20132 loss against [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] at [[Vale Park]].<ref name=\"September Goal of the Month\">{{cite web |title=September Goal of the Month winner is... |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/september-goal-of-the-month-winner-is...-1117135.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=16 October 2013}}</ref>\n* 24 \u2013 [[Callum Wilson (English footballer)|Callum Wilson]] won the September player of the month.<ref name=\"September Player of the Month is...\">{{cite web |title=September Player of the Month is... |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/wilson-wins-september-player-of-the-month-1132308.aspx |work=CCFC Official Site |date=24 October 2013}}</ref>\n* 30 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]'s [[FA Cup]] first round away tie against [[AFC Wimbledon]] was chosen for live television screening on [[BT Sport]]. The match will be played on Friday 8 November 2013.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sky Blues on TV for FA Cup |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/fa-cup-first-round-date-1144807.aspx |work=CCFC Official Site |date=30 October 2013}}</ref>\n* 31 \u2013 [[Callum Wilson (English footballer)|Callum Wilson]] signs a new contract to keep him at the club until June 2015 with the option to extend to 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Wilson pens new contract with Sky Blues |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/wilson-new-contract-1146028.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=31 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''November''':\n* 1 \u2013 [[Callum Wilson (English footballer)|Callum Wilson]] was named October's PFA Fan's Player of the Month for [[Football League One|League One]].<ref name=\"Wilson Wins PFA Fans' Player Of The Month\">{{Cite web |title=Wilson Wins PFA Fans' Player of the Month |url=http://www.coventrycity-mad.co.uk/news/tmnw/wilson_wins_pfa_fans_player_of_the_month_812560/index.shtml? |work=CoventryCityMAD |date=1 November 2013}}</ref>\n* 7 \u2013 [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] handed a squad number to Academy player [[Courtney Baker-Richardson]] ahead of the [[FA Cup]] fixture against [[AFC Wimbledon]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=City youngster given squad number |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/baker-richardson-squad-number-1161059.aspx? |work=CCFC Official Site |date=7 November 2013}}</ref>\n* 12 \u2013 [[Conor Thomas]] signs a new contract to keep him at the club until June 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Conor Thomas signs new deal |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/thomas-new-contract-1170240.aspx |work=CCFC Official Site |date=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n* 12 \u2013 [[Franck Moussa]] won the October goal of the month award for his delightful chip against [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]] in the 3\u20131 win on Tuesday, 22 October.<ref name=\"October Goal of the Month\">{{Cite web |title=Who's won Goal of the Month? |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/oct-goal-of-the-month-winner-1168528.aspx |work=CCFC Official Site |date=12 November 2013}}</ref>\n* 22 \u2013 [[Ryan Haynes (footballer)|Ryan Haynes]] signs a new contract to keep him at the club until June 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ryan Haynes pens new deal |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/article/haynes-new-contract-1187788.aspx |work=CCFC Official Site |date=22 November 2013}}</ref>\n* 22 \u2013 [[Billy Daniels (footballer)|Billy Daniels]] signs a new contract to keep him at the club until June 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sky Blues midfielder signs new contract |u